description: A 1:1 supramolecular complex formed via non-covalent interactions between 4-[(4-(n-hexyloxy)phenylimino)methyl]benzoic acid and 2-chloro-4-(pyridin-4-ylazo)phenyl 4-decyloxybenzoate.

A bowl-shaped macrocyclic organic molecule synthesized via the cyclotrimerization of veratrole followed by demethylation using boron tribromide. The structure features a rigid core composed of three catechol subunits linked by methylene bridges, decorated with six peripheral hydroxyl functional groups.

n-4O3 is an aromatic organic scaffold featuring a rigid core connected by linkers and substituted with flexible side chains. The structure includes heteroatom-containing functional groups and extended conjugation. Variations in ring composition and terminal groups modulate steric bulk and electronic distribution.

A conjugated copolymer consisting of a polythiophene backbone where separated thiophene units bearing styryl-triphenylamine pendants are spaced by unsubstituted tetrathienyl segments. The bulky pendants are designed to tune energy levels.

A rod-like molecule containing a polymerizable acrylate group linked via a hexamethylene spacer to a bis(benzoate) core, which is further connected to an azobenzene moiety bearing a carboxylic acid group. Synthesized by reacting a diazonium salt of 4-aminobenzoic acid with an aniline derivative.
An ester formed by the condensation of retinol and palmitic acid, featuring a long aliphatic chain attached to the retinyl polyene structure.
An organic molecule featuring a linear core of three phenyl rings connected by ester linkages, flanked on both ends by propyl chains that terminate in reactive acrylate groups.
A homopolymer synthesized via RAFT polymerization using di(ethylene glycol) methyl ether methacrylate. It serves as a model system for studying nonequilibrium assembly in aqueous environments.

A polymerizable organic monomer consisting of a methacrylate group tethered to a photochromic spiro-core. The core structure features an indoline ring spiro-fused to a benzopyran ring substituted with a nitro group. It is synthesized for incorporation into stimuli-responsive polymer networks.
A saturated oxygen-containing heterocycle bearing a pentyl chain. Produced via hydrogenation of the corresponding exocyclic alkene.

A segmented copolymer composed of poly(butylene succinate) hard blocks and soft units derived from dimerized fatty acids. This material is prepared with a specific weight ratio to balance rigidity and flexibility.

A bent-core organic compound with a hockey-stick geometry, featuring a central 3-amino-2-methylbenzoate unit. The molecule contains four phenyl rings connected by ester and azomethine linkages, terminating in a polar nitrile group and an octyloxy chain.

A symmetric perylene-3,4,9,10-tetracarboxylic diimide derivative in which the imide nitrogen atoms are substituted with 1,3-bis(2-(2-(2-methoxyethoxy)ethoxy)ethoxy)propan-2-yl groups, consisting of a planar pi-conjugated perylene core flanked by branched poly(ethylene glycol) tails.
A copolyamide synthesized from glycine, hexamethylenediamine, and adipic acid.

Lithium (decylsulfonyl)(trifluoromethanesulfonyl)imide is an aromatic organic scaffold featuring a rigid core connected by linkers and substituted with flexible side chains. The structure includes heteroatom-containing functional groups and extended conjugation, with substituent patterns defining the overall shape.
An oleamide derivative featuring a pyridine ring attached to the amide nitrogen via a methylene linker at the 2-position of the pyridine ring.
A meso-tetraarylporphyrin derivative substituted with meta-methoxy groups on the phenyl rings.

A silica nanoparticle featuring an ordered internal pore system, modified with N-(6-aminohexyl)aminopropylsilyl chains. The synthesis involves an ion-exchange strategy to anchor the long-chain diamine linker to the silica backbone. It is designed to act as a scaffold for loading gas-releasing functional groups.

A conjugated polymer featuring a polythiophene backbone functionalized with bi(thienylenevinylene) side chains attached via a vinyl linkage. Synthesized via Stille coupling, this material possesses extended conjugation in the pendants.

A symmetrical diepoxide molecule consisting of a central hydroquinone (p-phenylene) unit esterified on both sides by 4-hydroxybenzoic acid moieties, creating a three-ring aromatic core. This core is further extended at both ends by undecanoyl chains connected via ester linkages, with each aliphatic chain terminating in an oxirane (epoxide) ring.

4'-(3-cyclopentylpropoxy)-[1,1'-biphenyl]-4-carbonitrile is a nitrile derivative based on a rigid biphenyl core. The 4'-position bears a propoxy linker terminated by a cyclopentyl group. This structure combines an extended conjugated aromatic system with a flexible aliphatic side chain.

A zinc-metallated porphyrin derivative with four 4-(octyloxycarbonyl)phenyl substituents at the meso positions. Produced by reacting the free-base ligand with zinc acetate. The long octyl chains promote edge-on molecular stacking in solid-state assemblies.

Synthesized from diisopropylamine, this compound is a 2,4,5-trisubstituted thiazole. It is characterized by a bulky diisopropylamino group at the 2-position, a phenyl ring at the 4-position, and a methyl ester at the 5-position.

An asymmetric anhydride molecule in which a decanoyl group is linked via an anhydride bond to a 4-(decanoyloxy)benzoyl moiety. The structure features a central benzene ring substituted at the para positions with an ester-linked decyl chain and an anhydride-linked decyl chain.
A sterically crowded porphyrin with eight methyl groups on the pyrrole rings and bulky 3,5-di-tert-butylphenyl groups at the meso positions.

A tripeptide molecule composed of glutamic acid, cysteine, and glycine residues linked by peptide bonds. It contains a reactive thiol group and serves as a reducing agent in redox-sensitive material systems to cleave disulfide bonds.
A meta-substituted aromatic diacid chloride featuring an azo group bridging two benzene rings, synthesized for use in polycondensation.
An N-acylated lysine salt prepared via a caprolactam route. It features a sixteen-carbon palmitoyl chain attached to the alpha-nitrogen, giving it significant hydrophobic character.
A thioamide derivative of isonicotinic acid, structurally related to isoniazid but containing a 2-ethyl substituent.
Peptide-based compound forming hydrogel in water.

A symmetric dimer featuring an octamethylene spacer connecting two terminal anthracene moieties via Schiff base linkages, specifically formed by the condensation of 1,8-bis(4-formylphenoxy)-octane with 2-aminoanthracene.
A flavylium salt with a 7-dodecyloxy-6-methoxy A-ring and a 4-dodecylsulfanyl B-ring. It is a bent-shaped structural isomer of related linear flavylium cores.
A pyridine derivative functionalized with a hydrazide group at the 4-position. It is a synthetic antibiotic obtained by the reaction of ethyl isonicotinate with hydrazine.
A methylated dihydroxybenzene produced by the enzymatic hydroxylation of p-cresol.

A cationic amphiphile synthesized from spermine and pentyl acrylate, featuring a linear polyamine core with propyl and butyl spacers. The structure is fully alkylated to form four quaternary ammonium groups and six hydrophobic ester-terminated pentyl chains.
An organic ester characterized by a 4-methoxyphenyl group linked to a cyano-substituted acrylate backbone. It is utilized as a precursor in the formation of vinyl acetate copolymers.

A halogenated Schiff base compound synthesized from 7-iodo-6-aminocoumarin and a pyridyl-azo functionalized salicylaldehyde. It comprises a coumarin scaffold substituted with an iodine atom, linked via an imine group to a phenol ring bearing a pyridyl-azo substituent. The presence of the iodine atom enables halogen bonding interactions, influencing its self-assembly into supramolecular networks. It functions as a gelator and a sensor for specific ions.
A room-temperature carbazole liquid obtained by attaching a 2-ethylhexyl (2-C2C6) chain to the nitrogen atom; used as a liquid-emitting layer in OLEDs.

An unsymmetrical azomethine derivative comprising a central benzene-1,4-dicarboxaldehyde-derived core linked to a pyren-1-amine unit at one terminus and a 4-dodecylaniline moiety at the other. The structure features a bulky pyrene group and a phenyl ring substituted with a dodecyl chain, connected via imine linkages.

An organic compound featuring a central azo linkage connecting two aromatic rings. The structure consists of a benzamide core substituted at the para position of the benzoyl ring with a (4-hexyloxyphenyl)diazenyl group. The amide nitrogen is substituted with a 4-fluorophenyl group. The molecule terminates at one end with a hexyloxy chain and at the other with a fluorine atom, while the amide functionality provides sites for intermolecular hydrogen bonding.

This compound is an organic salt featuring a central imidazolium cation and a tetrafluoroborate anion. The cationic core consists of a positively charged imidazole ring substituted at both nitrogen atoms. One nitrogen bears a methyl group, while the other is attached to a phenyl ring at the 1-position. This phenyl ring is further substituted at the para position with a dodecyloxy group, consisting of a twelve-carbon alkyl chain linked via an oxygen atom. The overall structure is charge-balanced by the BF4− counterion.

1O2 is an aromatic organic scaffold with a rigid core connected by linkers and substituted with flexible side chains. It includes heteroatom groups and extended conjugation, with substituents defining shape and polarity. Ring composition and terminal groups modulate steric bulk and electronic distribution.

Disodium oleyl polyoxyethylene(5) ether sulfosuccinate is an anionic surfactant molecule characterized by a hydrophobic C18 oleyl tail containing a single internal carbon–carbon double bond. This lipophilic chain is connected via an ether linkage to a hydrophilic poly(ethylene oxide) spacer consisting of five –CH2CH2O– repeat units. The terminal oxygen of this polyether segment forms an ester bond with one of the carbonyl groups of a succinate-derived backbone (substituted butanedioate). The succinate core features a sulfonate group (–SO3−) attached directly to the carbon chain and a terminal carboxylate group. The molecule exists as a dianion, with the negative charges on the sulfonate and carboxylate groups balanced by two sodium cations.
Class III glass former. Exhibited melting and crystallization under humid storage conditions. Demonstrated high hygroscopicity.

A sulfur-containing organic semiconductor based on a dinaphtho-thieno-thiophene fused ring system, functionalized with two linear decyl alkyl chains. The rigid heteroaromatic core promotes strong intermolecular pi-pi interactions.
A macrocyclic organic compound consisting of a central porphyrin core substituted at the four meso positions with 4-dodecyloxyphenyl groups.

A lysine-based surfactant synthesized via the reaction of octanoyl chloride with alpha-amino-epsilon-caprolactam. It consists of an eight-carbon alkyl chain attached to the alpha-amine of a lysine sodium salt.
A fully aromatic polymer consisting of repeating units formed by the condensation of p-phenylenediamine and terephthaloyl chloride, featuring rigid para-phenylene rings linked by amide groups.

Synthesized by condensing terephthalohydrazide with 4-formylphenyl 3,4-bis(dodecyloxy)benzoate. The molecule has an extended rigid core containing both hydrazone and ester functional groups, terminated by four dodecyloxy chains.

This amphiphilic compound features a 2-butyloctyl hydrophobic tail and a polar imidazolium-functionalized glucose head group. A triethylene glycol spacer with a terminal azide is attached to the imidazolium cation, facilitating bio-orthogonal conjugation.

A polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbon consisting of an anthracene core substituted with phenyl rings at the 2 and 6 positions. The molecule features an extended pi-conjugated system utilized in organic electronics.
A random copolymer containing both 2,5-pyridinedicarboxylate and terephthalate units in the central polyester block, synthesized with propylene glycol and capped with PEG-2000.

A supramolecular complex formed by the 1:1 molar association of 4-[(4-hexyloxyphenyl)iminomethyl]benzoic acid and 4-[2-(pyridin-4-yl)diazenyl]-3-methylphenyl 4-dodecyloxybenzoate. The structure consists of a five-ring aromatic core assembled via intermolecular hydrogen bonding between the carboxylic acid group of the benzoic acid derivative and the pyridine nitrogen of the azo ester component. The molecular architecture features azo, imine, and ester linking groups, a lateral methyl substituent on the central phenyl ring of the pyridine-containing component, and terminal hexyloxy and dodecyloxy alkyl chains.
A saturated dicarboxylic acid produced by the hydrogenation of muconic acid, primarily used in nylon production.
A sterol found in fungi membranes such as Pleurotus ostreatus. It contains a tetracyclic core with a side chain, capable of forming lamellar or rod-like nanostructures.

A thiazole derivative synthesized via a one-pot chemoenzymatic reaction involving diethylamine, benzoyl isothiocyanate, and dimethyl acetylenedicarboxylate. The molecule features a central thiazole ring substituted with a phenyl group at position 4, a methyl ester at position 5, and a diethylamino moiety at position 2.
A C3-symmetric, tri-chlorinated rigid scaffold synthesized via cycloaddition of 1,8-dichloroanthracene with a chlorobenzyne intermediate.

PET-5O is an aromatic organic scaffold featuring a rigid core connected by linkers and substituted with flexible side chains. The structure includes heteroatom-containing functional groups and extended conjugation. Variations in ring composition and terminal groups modulate steric bulk and electronic distribution.

A symmetric dimeric molecule comprising a central V-shaped five-ring aromatic segment connected to two peripheral triphenylene cores via dodecyl alkyl tethers. The molecule is constructed by esterifying a triphenylene-functionalized benzoic acid with a central resorcinol-derived bis-phenol. It features multiple ester linkages and long alkoxy chains.

A hybrid nanomaterial consisting of a gold core functionalized with biphenyl derivatives bearing a terminal nitrile group. The organic shell is anchored to the metal surface through a sulfur atom and a dodecyl spacer.

A holmium(III) coordination species comprising three dibenzoylmethane ligands and a bound water molecule surrounding the metal center. This seven-coordinate complex serves as a core structural motif without peripheral alkyl chains, organizing into linear arrays via hydrogen bonds in the solid state.

A C3-symmetric organic molecule comprising a hexadehydrotribenzo[12]annulene core substituted with three pentadecanamide side chains. The molecule features a rigid, planar pi-system containing triple bonds and amide groups that facilitate the formation of supramolecular assemblies through intermolecular hydrogen bonding. It exhibits polymorphism, forming lamellar crystalline phases or nanofibrous aggregates depending on preparation conditions.
A fluorinated molecule comprising a sulfonic acid headgroup and a perfluorinated ether chain terminated with an iodoethyl segment.
An imidazoline derivative containing a phenolic moiety and a substituted amine linker.
A gold(III) porphyrin salt with hexadecyloxy chains and a hexafluorophosphate counterion.

Compound 10 is an aromatic organic scaffold featuring a rigid core connected by linkers and substituted with flexible side chains. The structure includes heteroatom-containing functional groups and extended conjugation, with substituent patterns defining the overall shape and polarity. Variations in ring composition and terminal groups modulate steric bulk and electronic distribution across the framework.
A square-planar coordination complex containing a gold(III) ion coordinated to a meso-tetrakis(4-octyloxyphenyl)porphyrin ligand, balanced by a chloride counterion.

A symmetrical diester molecule consisting of a central terephthalate core linked to two 4-(6-acryloyloxyhexyloxy)phenyl groups, where each terminal phenol ring is substituted with a hexyl chain ending in an acrylate ester.

Molecular structure: The molecule is a symmetric bis-amide built around a central para-disubstituted benzene (terephthaloyl) core. Each of the two carbonyl groups on this core forms an amide linkage (–C(=O)–NH–) to a terminal phenyl ring. Each terminal phenyl ring bears two additional substituents: one phenolic hydroxyl group (–OH) and one carboxylic acid group (–C(=O)OH), giving two hydroxyl groups and two carboxylic acid groups overall.

Synthesis: It can be assembled by forming two amide bonds between an activated terephthalic-acid derivative (commonly the diacyl chloride or another activated diacid equivalent) and an aniline-type precursor in which the aromatic ring already carries hydroxyl and carboxylic-acid substituents. The preparation is a double acylation/condensation, typically conducted under basic conditions to neutralize the acid generated during amide formation, yielding the symmetric terephthaloyl diamide.

A semiconducting polymer comprising isoindigo acceptor moieties alternating with (E)-1,2-bis(thiophen-2-yl)ethene (TVT) donor units. The polymer backbone is solubilized by bulky 2-decyltetradecyl alkyl chains attached to the isoindigo core.
A porphyrin derivative substituted with thienyl groups at the meso positions and methyl groups on the pyrrole beta-positions, absorbing in the near-IR region.
A synthetic amphiphile consisting of a gentiobiose headgroup attached to a di-myristoyl glycerol backbone. The headgroup comprises two glucose units linked by a beta-(1->6) glycosidic bond.

Molecular structure: The compound consists of a citrate trianion paired with a calcium dication. The citrate unit is a three-carbon backbone bearing three carboxylate groups (one terminal carboxylate and two carboxylates on the substituted carbon framework) and one hydroxyl group on the central carbon, giving an overall 3− charge on the organic ligand. The Ca2+ center is present as the counter-cation and can be depicted as ionically associated/coordinate-bound to the carboxylate oxygen atoms of the citrate.

Synthesis: Calcium citrate complex can be prepared by acid–base neutralization of citric acid with a calcium base such as calcium carbonate, calcium hydroxide, or calcium oxide. In a typical preparation, citric acid is dissolved in water and a stoichiometric amount of the calcium source is added with stirring to generate the citrate carboxylate anions and introduce Ca2+. The resulting calcium–citrate salt/complex is isolated from the reaction mixture by separating the solid product and removing residual inorganic byproducts (e.g., carbon dioxide release when using carbonate, or water formed during neutralization), followed by washing and drying.
An N-aryl acrylamide featuring a 4-chlorophenyl moiety and a cyclohexenyl ring. This compound is synthesized as a precursor for hexahydrophenanthridinone formation.
A gold(III) porphyrin derivative with dodecyloxy groups, paired with a pentacyanocyclopentadienide anion.
A chlorine-substituted ethyl 2-cyano-3-phenyl-2-propenoate with the halogen at the 4-position. It is produced via the reaction of 4-chlorobenzaldehyde and ethyl cyanoacetate.
A synthetic benzoic acid derivative comprising a tetrahydronaphthalene moiety substituted with methyl groups and a vinyl bond linking to the aromatic acid.

A cationic organic salt comprising a triphenylene aromatic system connected to a trimethylammonium headgroup via a propylene ether linker. Synthesized by the quaternization of a bromo-substituted precursor, this molecule acts as an emitting species in supramolecular assemblies.

This compound consists of a cationic gold(III) porphyrin complex, specifically gold(III) meso-tetrakis(4-hexadecyloxyphenyl)porphyrin, paired electrostatically with a pentacyanocyclopentadienide anion. The cation features a central gold(III) ion coordinated within a porphyrin macrocycle that is substituted at the meso positions with four phenyl rings, each bearing a para-hexadecyloxy (C16) alkyl chain.
An aliphatic polyamide formed by the condensation of decamethylenediamine and dodecanedioic acid.

4'-(3-cycloheptylpropoxy)-[1,1'-biphenyl]-4-carbonitrile is a biphenyl derivative with a rigid aromatic core. It features a 4-cyano group and a 4'-(3-cycloheptylpropoxy) ether chain. The structure combines extended conjugation with a flexible aliphatic linker terminating in a cycloheptyl ring.

A fluorinated organic compound consisting of a central 3-hydroxy-5-methylbenzoate core connected to a 4-dodecyloxyphenyl group through an imine linkage and to a 2,3,4,5-tetrafluorophenyl ring via an ester linkage, featuring a long dodecyloxy tail.

A fluorinated derivative of 7,7,8,8-tetracyanoquinodimethane (TCNQ) featuring four fluorine atoms on the quinoid ring. It serves as a strong electron acceptor and is widely used as a p-type dopant for organic semiconductors.

A fused heteroacene consisting of a central furan ring fused with two thiophene rings, symmetrically substituted with 4-propylphenyl groups. It is prepared via a copper-catalysed cascade C–S coupling and ring closure reaction using sodium sulfide.
A dimethoxylated phenolic aldehyde derived from hardwood lignin, used as a chemical building block for bio-based resins.
A functionalized benzoic acid derivative synthesized by reacting 4-hydroxy-3-methoxybenzoic acid with acetic anhydride, featuring both methoxy and acetoxy substituents on the aromatic ring.
A benzoic acid derivative featuring a hexadecanoyl (palmitoyl) chain attached via an ester linkage at the para position relative to the carboxylic acid group.

A zinc-coordinated porphyrin macrocycle featuring four meso-phenyl groups substituted with butoxycarbonyl chains. It is synthesized by metallation of the free-base porphyrin with zinc acetate. The molecule serves as a solution-processable organic semiconductor for thin-film applications.
An aromatic diterpene acid found in conifers. It organizes into rod-like microparticles, with stacking interactions influenced by its aromatic ring.
A dimer molecule consisting of two terminal pyrene units linked via iminomethylidene groups to phenoxy moieties, which are connected by a central nonamethylene spacer.

Molecular structure: This compound contains two benzene rings connected through an aryl–ester linkage (a benzoyloxy connection), giving a diaryl diester framework. One ring bears a hexyloxy substituent (an O–(CH2)5CH3 ether) and also carries a carbonyl group that is esterified to the phenoxy oxygen of the second ring. The second benzene ring bears a para-substituted carboxylate ester, where the carboxyl carbonyl is bonded to an oxygen that is further connected to a chiral (S)-2-octyl group (an O–CH(CH3)–(CH2)5CH3 substituent).

Synthesis: A plausible preparation is based on stepwise formation of the ether and the two ester bonds. The hexyloxy substituent can be introduced by O-alkylation (Williamson ether synthesis) of a hydroxybenzoic/benzoyl precursor with a hexyl electrophile. The inter-ring benzoyloxy ester can be formed by acylation of a phenolic hydroxyl group on one ring with an activated benzoic-acid derivative (e.g., an acid chloride) bearing the hexyloxy substituent. Finally, the remaining benzoic-acid group on the second ring can be esterified with enantiomerically enriched (S)-2-octanol (or by coupling the acid with the alcohol using a standard esterification/condensation method) to furnish the chiral alkyl benzoate.
A cyclohexanol derivative substituted at the para position with a bulky tert-butyl group.

A quaternary ammonium salt consisting of a propyl backbone where the 2- and 3-positions are substituted with oleyl groups via ether linkages, and the 1-position is attached to an N,N,N-trimethylammonium group.

A star-shaped oligomer consisting of a central triazatruxene core functionalized at the 2, 7, and 12 positions with three peripheral triazatruxene units via propargylic alcohol linkers. It is synthesized by the nucleophilic addition of the lithiated species of 2-ethynyl-5,10,15-triethyl-10,15-dihydro-5H-diindolo[3,2-a:3',2'-c]carbazole to 2,7,12-triformyl-5,10,15-triethyl-10,15-dihydro-5H-diindolo[3,2-a:3',2'-c]carbazole. The molecule features ethyl chains on the nitrogen atoms to promote solubility and chiral secondary alcohol centers in the bridging units.

This chemical entity is an acrylanilide derivative that incorporates a quinoline moiety into its molecular framework. It is isolated as a solid compound. The structure is used to investigate the specific effects of heteroaromatic substituents.

A gold(III) porphyrin complex in which the central Au(III) ion is coordinated by the four nitrogen atoms of the porphyrin macrocycle and balanced by a chloride counterion. The porphyrin core is substituted at the four meso-positions with 4-(icosyloxy)phenyl groups, featuring long C20 alkyl chains attached via ether linkages.
A wholly aromatic polyamide-hydrazide prepared from meta-oriented monomers, characterized by increased solubility in polar aprotic solvents compared to its para-oriented analogue.

A paramagnetic square-planar copper(II) complex coordinated by a 3,6-di-tert-butylcatecholate dianion and a 4,4'-di-tert-butyl-2,2'-bipyridine ligand. It is synthesized via a one-pot reaction involving metallic copper, the corresponding ortho-quinone, and the bipyridine in tetrahydrofuran. The molecule crystallizes in a lamellar structure without pi-stacking interactions.
A natural steroid hormone featuring a tetracyclic skeleton with an aromatic A-ring, a phenolic hydroxyl group, and a secondary alcohol on the D-ring.
A diester molecule featuring a central terephthalate core linked to two phenolic rings, with each ring attached to an undecyl spacer chain terminating in an acrylate group.

An aromatic polyester polymer composed of repeating units formed from 2,6-naphthalenedicarboxylic acid and 1,4-butanediol. The structural backbone features a rigid 2,6-naphthalene moiety connected by flexible aliphatic butylene segments via ester linkages.
A heterocyclic compound featuring a morpholine ring attached to a thiazole core. It is synthesized using dimethyl acetylenedicarboxylate and bears a methyl ester and a phenyl substituent.

An aromatic organic molecule featuring a benzoic acid hexyl ester core substituted at the 3 and 5 positions with long alkoxy chains terminating in hexylamide groups. The structure combines a rigid aromatic ring with flexible alkyl spacers and hydrogen-bonding amide functionalities, allowing for self-assembly into fibrous networks or ribbons in various solvents. It is synthesized via the alkylation of 3,5-dihydroxybenzoic acid ester with bifunctional spacers followed by amidation.

A molecular entity featuring an isobutyl ester and a diphenylphosphoryl group, formed by the addition of a secondary phosphine oxide to a terminal alkyne. It serves as a functionalized monomer with potential for further derivation.
A meso-tetraarylporphyrin derivative substituted with para-amino groups on the phenyl rings.

Prepared by the condensation of stearic acid with 11-azido-3,6,9-trioxaundecan-1-amine. An amide-linked conjugate consisting of a long hydrophobic stearyl tail and a hydrophilic PEG-like spacer terminated with a reactive azide group.
A benzoic acid derivative featuring a methacrylate group linked via a hexyloxy chain. Prepared by esterification of 4-(6-hydroxyhexyloxy)benzoic acid with methacrylic acid.

An alkali metal carboxylate formed by the reaction of cesium carbonate with a cis-unsaturated fatty acid. Utilized as a soluble cesium source in the high-temperature synthesis of inorganic nanocrystals.

4'-(cyclohexylmethoxy)-[1,1'-biphenyl]-4-carbonitrile is a nitrile-substituted biphenyl derivative. The molecule features a rigid aromatic core substituted at the 4-position with a cyano group and at the 4'-position with a flexible cyclohexylmethoxy ether chain. It contains both aromatic and cycloaliphatic rings.
Rod-like nanoparticles consisting of linear polysaccharide chains of beta-1,4-linked D-glucose units with surface sulfate ester groups.
A phospholipid consisting of a glycerol backbone esterified at the sn-1 and sn-2 positions with two saturated long-chain fatty acids, and linked at the sn-3 position to a phosphorylcholine moiety.

A glycosylated azobenzene derivative consisting of a mannobioside disaccharide unit linked to the phenolic oxygen of a phenylazophenol core. Synthesized via sequential glycosylation, this molecule functions as a photoswitchable ligand for bacterial lectins, utilizing the isomerization of the azo group to modulate binding.
A rod-shaped organic ester consisting of a rigid aromatic carboxylic acid core functionalized with a flexible hexyl chain at the para position via an ester linkage.

N-(4-(Dimethylamino)phenyl)cyclohex-1-ene-1-carboxamide (S15) is an aromatic organic scaffold featuring a rigid core connected by linkers and substituted with flexible side chains. The structure includes heteroatom-containing functional groups and extended conjugation, with substituent patterns defining the overall shape and polarity. Variations in ring composition and terminal groups modulate steric bulk and electronic distribution across the framework.

A random copolymer synthesized via RAFT polymerization containing methyl acryloyl-di-L-phenylalanine and N,N-dimethylacrylamide. The incorporation of the diphenylalanine moiety promotes hydrophobic collapse and self-assembly.

Compound 8 is an aromatic organic scaffold featuring a rigid core connected by linkers and substituted with flexible side chains. The structure includes heteroatom-containing functional groups and extended conjugation. Ring composition and terminal groups modulate steric bulk and electronic distribution.

An asymmetric second-generation dendron based on a 3,5-dihydroxybenzyl alcohol core. It contains two distinct dendritic sectors: one sector is functionalized with two dodecyl chains, and the other sector bears two amino-nitro-substituted azobenzene units attached through tetra(ethylene glycol) spacers.

1,3,5-Tris(2-furyl)benzene consists of a central benzene ring bearing three identical heteroaryl substituents at the 1,3,5-positions. Each substituent is a furan ring (a five-membered aromatic ring containing one oxygen atom) attached through its 2-position to the benzene core via a carbon–carbon single bond, giving a C3-symmetric triaryl framework. The compound was prepared by a palladium-catalyzed Suzuki–Miyaura cross-coupling in which 1,3,5-triiodobenzene was reacted with furan-2-boronic acid in the presence of Pd(PPh3)4, forming three new C(sp2)–C(sp2) bonds between the benzene core and the 2-furyl groups.
A regioregular conjugated macromolecule consisting of thiophene rings substituted with hexyl chains, prepared via established synthetic protocols for electronic applications.

A donor-acceptor alternating copolymer comprising electron-rich benzodithiophene units and electron-deficient fluorinated dithienylbenzothiadiazole moieties. The fluorine substitution promotes strong interchain interactions.

An organic salt comprising a positively charged five-membered nitrogen-containing heterocycle substituted with two linear eighteen-carbon alkyl chains, paired with a bromide counterion. The compound features a symmetric cationic core with extensive hydrophobic aliphatic tails.

A macrocyclic organic molecule featuring a naphthalene core and an azobenzene unit connected by oxyethylene tethers. This planar chiral compound is synthesized via the reductive debromination of a halogenated precursor and acts as a chiral switch.

A dinitro-substituted organic compound characterized by a rod-like core containing a diazo group and an amide linkage. The structure consists of an (E)-4-[4-(4-hexyloxy)phenylazo]benzoyl moiety connected to a phenyl ring decorated with two electron-withdrawing nitro groups at the ortho and para positions relative to the amide nitrogen.
A phosphatidylcholine compound having a stearoyl group at the 1-position and a 15-hydroxyeicosatetraenoyl group at the 2-position of the sn-glycerol backbone.
A semi-aromatic polyamide synthesized from decamethylenediamine and terephthalic acid, featuring a backbone with both aromatic rings and aliphatic chains.
A chlorinated nitrobenzoic acid derivative with substituents at the 2 and 5 positions. It is utilized in the investigation of solid solution formation and crystallizes in the monoclinic system.

The molecular structure consists of an N-alkylated carbazole unit, which is a fused tricyclic aromatic system containing one ring nitrogen, bearing a long, linear alkyl substituent on the nitrogen. This carbazole aromatic framework is C–C bonded to a thiophene ring. The thiophene is further substituted by a benzothiadiazole unit (a fused bicyclic system containing a benzene ring fused to a five-membered ring with two nitrogens and one sulfur), which is in turn C–C bonded to another thiophene ring, forming a repeating conjugated backbone of alternating carbazole and dithienylbenzothiadiazole units.

A polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbon consisting of four benzene rings fused to form an eight-membered central ring. Synthesized via palladium-catalyzed direct arylation and cyclization of 2-iodobiphenyl. Features a non-planar, saddle-shaped molecular geometry.

A supramolecular complex formed by the 1:1 molar association of 4-[2-(pyridin-4-yl)diazenyl]-3-methylphenyl 4-octyloxybenzoate and 4-[(4-hexyloxyphenyl)iminomethyl]benzoic acid. The assembly is stabilized by intermolecular hydrogen bonding between the carboxylic acid moiety of the benzoic acid derivative and the pyridine nitrogen atom of the azo ester. The overall structure features a five-ring aromatic core connected by azo, imine, and ester linkages, with a lateral methyl group on the central phenyl ring of the base component, and is terminated by hexyloxy and octyloxy alkyl chains.

A quaternary ammonium compound consisting of a propane-1,2,3-triol (glycerol) backbone where the hydroxyl groups at positions 1 and 2 are esterified with oleic acid chains, and the position 3 hydroxyl is replaced by a trimethylammonium group.
An acetanilide derivative comprising a benzene ring substituted with a hydroxyl group para to an acetamido group.

A symmetrical linear monomer consisting of a 2,4-hexadiyne core terminated by two acrylate ester groups. Synthesized via the reaction of 2,4-hexadiyne-1,6-diol with acryloyl chloride, this molecule features a conjugated system of triple bonds flanked by polymerizable vinyl groups. It serves as a precursor for forming cross-linked organic networks upon exposure to UV irradiation.
A fully aromatic polyamide prepared from m-phenylenediamine and isophthaloyl chloride, containing meta-phenylene linkages.
An isoquinolinesulfonamide derivative containing a homopiperazine ring.

A fluorinated organolithium salt featuring an imide anion where the nitrogen center bridges a trifluoromethylsulfonyl group and a nonafluorobutylsulfonyl chain. It is utilized as a highly stable ionic source in solid polymer matrices.

A supramolecular complex formed by the 1:1 molar association of 4-[(4-hexyloxyphenyl)iminomethyl]benzoic acid and 4-[2-(pyridin-4-yl)diazenyl]-3-methylphenyl 4-hexadecyloxybenzoate via intermolecular hydrogen bonding between the carboxylic acid group and the pyridine nitrogen. The assembly features a five-ring aromatic core incorporating azo, imine, and ester linkages, with a lateral methyl substituent on the central phenyl ring of the pyridine-containing component, and is terminated by hexyloxy and hexadecyloxy alkyl chains.
A fully thioether-functionalized flavylium salt with three chains on the A-ring and one on the B-ring, synthesized via cyclocondensation chemistry.
A discrete dimeric complex salt featuring two samarium(III) ions bridged by acetate ligands, crystallized with two 1-ethyl-3-methylimidazolium cations.
DOBA. Forms hydrogen bonded dimers in the crystalline state.
The molecule features a triphenylene core substituted with four hexyloxy chains and two 4-hydroxybutoxy chains terminating in hydroxyl groups.

A planar polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbon derivative featuring a hexaazapentacene core fused with four benzene rings and substituted with two dodecyl chains. It is known to self-assemble into hollow cylindrical nanostructures in solution.

A steroid derivative in which the hydroxy group of beta-sitosterol has been converted to the corresponding ester by reaction with the carboxy group of 4-iodocinnamic acid. The molecule comprises a rigid tetracyclic steroidal core with a branched alkyl chain containing an ethyl group at the C24 position, linked to a 3-(4-iodophenyl)prop-2-enoyl moiety.
A chelating surfactant molecule comprising a dodecyl-substituted cresol unit linked to an iminodiacetate headgroup, used for metal ion coordination and formation of self-assembled films on surfaces.

A diacyl glycerophospholipid comprising a glycerol backbone esterified with a mixture of fatty acids at the sn-1 and sn-2 positions, and a phosphocholine moiety at the sn-3 position. The structure features a zwitterionic headgroup and typically contains unsaturated fatty acyl chains at the sn-2 position.

A chiral diester molecule comprising a biphenyl-4-carboxylate core esterified with a phenol derivative. The structure features a 4'-butyryl group (a propyl ketone) at one terminus of the biphenyl system. The other terminus consists of a phenyl ring substituted with a pentyl lactate moiety, specifically an (S)-1-(pentyloxy)-1-oxopropan-2-yloxy carbonyl group.
An organic molecule comprising a bicyclo[2.2.2]octane core symmetrically substituted at the 1 and 4 positions with two 4-heptanoyloxyphenyl groups.

Ethyl 2-cyano-3-(4-butoxyphenyl)-2-propenoate is an aromatic organic scaffold featuring a rigid core connected by linkers and substituted with flexible side chains. The structure includes heteroatom-containing functional groups and extended conjugation, with substituent patterns defining the overall shape and polarity. Variations in ring composition and terminal groups modulate steric bulk and electronic distribution across the framework.
A pyrazine analogue of nicotinamide. It is synthesized by the hydrolysis of pyrazinecarbonitrile or catalytic amidation of pyrazinecarboxylic acid.

A macrocyclic structure incorporating a 2,6-dibromo-1,5-dihydroxynaphthalene moiety bridged to an azobenzene group through ether linkages. It possesses planar chirality and serves as a heavy-atom-containing precursor for X-ray crystallographic assignment of stereochemistry.

Compound 7 is an aromatic organic scaffold with a rigid core connected by linkers and substituted with flexible side chains. Its structure includes heteroatom-containing functional groups and extended conjugation. Variations in ring composition and terminal groups modulate steric bulk and electronic distribution.
A rigid, helical rod-like polymer featuring a polyisocyanide backbone decorated with 4-octylphenyl groups.

A semi-crystalline fluoropolymer consisting of repeating vinylidene fluoride units with carbon-fluorine bonds. It exhibits multiple crystalline polymorphs, including non-polar alpha and polar beta forms, and is widely used for its piezoelectric properties. Synthesized via free-radical polymerization of the corresponding monomer.

A highly substituted hydroxypropyl cellulose derivative containing a large proportion of bulky 3,5-bis(trifluoromethyl)phenyl carbamate moieties and propionate esters, synthesized via reaction with the corresponding isocyanate and acid chloride.

This compound functions as an ester analogue of acrylanilide substrates. It is structurally formed from the condensation of phenol and cyclohex-1-ene-1-carboxylic acid. The substance exists as a solid.

A halogenated cyclic ketone derivative synthesized by reacting cyclohexanone with 2,4-dichlorobenzaldehyde. The molecular architecture consists of a six-membered carbonyl ring flanked by two 2,4-dichlorophenyl moieties linked through exocyclic double bonds, resulting in a cross-conjugated dienone system.
An aliphatic polyamide synthesized through the polycondensation of hexamethylenediamine and adipic acid.
A thioamide derivative of isonicotinic acid, structurally characterized by a propyl group at the 2-position of the pyridine ring.
A modified cellulosic polymer consisting of a hydroxypropyl cellulose backbone where the hydroxyl groups are substituted with propionate esters and 4-(trifluoromethyl)phenyl carbamate moieties.
A peptide comprising an N-terminal acetyl group attached to an L-aspartic acid residue, followed by a sequence of six L-alanine residues, and terminating in a C-terminal amide group.
A triblock copolymer consisting of a central poly(propylene oxide) chain flanked by two poly(ethylene oxide) chains.
A symmetrical diol consisting of a rigid o-tolidine core connected to two terminal phenyl rings through imine bonds. Each terminal ring is substituted with a 4-hydroxybutoxy chain.
A meso-tetraarylporphyrin derivative substituted with meta-nitro groups on the phenyl rings.
A pyrazinecarboxamide derivative and analogue of amiloride, featuring a phenyl-substituted guanidine group. It acts as a stimulator of osteoblast differentiation.
A synthetic oxazolidinone antimicrobial agent containing a morpholine ring and a fluorophenyl group linked to the oxazolidinone core.

CB8OCB is an aromatic organic scaffold featuring a rigid core connected by linkers and flexible side chains. The structure includes heteroatom-containing groups and extended conjugation. Additionally, ring compositions and terminal groups modulate the steric bulk and electronic distribution.
A polymer featuring a cyclohexyl group attached to the ether oxygen, prepared via controlled cationic polymerization. Its thermal analysis reveals a softening point above ambient conditions.

C12OPh-BH2 comprises a rigid aromatic core connected by linkers and substituted with flexible side chains. The structure features heteroatom-containing functional groups and extended conjugation. Terminal groups and substituent patterns modulate the steric bulk and electronic distribution.
Peptide-based compound forming hydrogel in water or PBS.

A magnesium-coordinated tetraazaporphyrin macrocycle decorated with eight peripheral ethylsulfanyl groups. This planar heterocyclic compound is synthesized for use in optoelectronics and serves as a model for studying electronic structures via magnetic circular dichroism.
Inorganic-organic hybrid nanoparticles possessing a plate-like morphology, composed of a calcium carbonate core structured with sodium dodecyl sulfonate and poly(acrylic acid).
A symmetrical dihaloalkane with a central pentyl substituent. Prepared via reaction of 3-pentylpentane-1,5-diol with hydrobromic acid.

A supramolecular complex formed by the 1:1 molar association of 4-[2-(pyridin-4-yl)diazenyl]-3-methylphenyl 4-dodecyloxybenzoate and 4-[(4-octyloxyphenyl)iminomethyl]benzoic acid. The structure is stabilized by intermolecular hydrogen bonding between the carboxylic acid group of the benzoic acid derivative and the pyridine nitrogen of the azo ester. The resulting assembly features a five-ring aromatic core connected by azo, imine, and ester linkages, with a lateral methyl group on the central phenyl ring of the pyridine-containing component, and is terminated by octyloxy and dodecyloxy alkyl chains.

A surfactant with a bulky 2-hexyldecyl tail and a cationic imidazolium-linked glucose head group. The imidazolium nitrogen is substituted with an azide-terminated diethylene glycol chain, designed for click coupling reactions.
A triterpenoid acid found in Melastoma candidum. It is observed to aggregate into uniform spherical nanoparticles through intermolecular forces.

A beta-lactam antibiotic synthesized via enzymatic reaction in a continuous-flow microfluidic device. Its structure features a bicyclic core comprising a four-membered lactam ring fused to a six-membered dihydrothiazine ring, substituted with a phenylglycine side chain.
An organic-inorganic hybrid perovskite material composed of a methylammonium cation cage within a lead iodide framework, utilized extensively in photovoltaics and optoelectronics.
A heteroaryl-substituted fused ring system where the central dithienofuran unit is flanked by two thiophen-3-yl groups. Synthesized using a copper-catalyzed cyclization strategy.
A highly substituted porphyrin with eight methyl groups on the pyrrole rings and four para-tert-butylphenyl groups at the meso positions.
A diacyl peroxide consisting of two benzoyl groups connected by a peroxide bond, commonly used as a radical initiator.
A phosphorylated derivative of alpha-tocopherol comprising a chroman head group substituted with a phosphate moiety and a hydrophobic phytyl tail attached at the C2 position.

A sulfobetaine inner salt featuring a dodecyl chain attached to a quaternary ammonium center, which is further substituted by two methyl groups and a butylene spacer connecting to a terminal sulfonate group.

A trisubstituted polycyclic aromatic ether. Synthesized by the palladium-catalyzed cross-reaction of differing iodobiaryl precursors. Features three methoxy groups attached to a saddle-shaped tetraphenylene core.

A polycyclic aromatic azo compound comprising a 1,1'-binaphthyl framework bridged by a diazocine unit with a nitrogen-nitrogen double bond. Synthesized via oxidative transformation of a hydrazine precursor, this rigid molecule features a constrained cis-azo geometry and is investigated for its optical properties.
A sulfur-containing organic molecule with a thioether linkage in the side chain. The core structure is a substituted oxazolone ring with a quaternary carbon bearing a phenyl ester.
A pyrazolopyrimidinone heterocycle substituted with a methylpiperazinylsulfonyl group and an ethoxyphenyl ether.

Synthesized via the esterification of 10-undecynoic acid with tetraethylene glycol monomethyl ether. The molecule contains a terminal alkyne group, a hydrophobic undecyl chain, and a hydrophilic methylated polyether tail connected by an ester linkage.

An azo-based benzamide derivative featuring a rigid core composed of three phenyl rings connected by an azo group and an amide linkage. The structure includes a hexyloxy chain attached to one terminal phenyl ring, while the opposite terminal phenyl ring bears an ortho-fluorine substituent relative to the amide nitrogen.
A substituted benzohydrazide derivative featuring an amino group and a hydroxyl group on the benzene ring, used as a precursor for aromatic polymers.

1O3 is an aromatic scaffold with a rigid core connected by linkers and substituted with flexible side chains. It features heteroatoms and extended conjugation, where substituents define shape and polarity. Ring composition and terminal groups modulate steric bulk and electronic distribution.

Synthesized via Sonogashira coupling using 4-ethynyl-4'-pentylbiphenyl, this extended conjugated system possesses a pyrene core and four biphenyl-ethynyl substituents, exhibiting strong pi-stacking capabilities.

A zinc-containing porphyrinoid derivative featuring a central Zn(II) ion and a periphery fully substituted with ethylthio moieties. The molecule is characterized by its potential applications in organic photovoltaics and nonlinear optics.

A zwitterionic methacrylate monomer that mimics the polar headgroup of phospholipids found in cell membranes. It is highly water-soluble and used to synthesize biocompatible polymers that can modify interfacial properties.
A discrete dimeric complex salt featuring two europium(III) ions bridged by acetate ligands, crystallized with two 1-ethyl-3-methylimidazolium cations.
POBA. Forms hydrogen bonded dimers in the crystalline state.

A methacrylate-based polymer electrolyte featuring a decyl spacer and a terminal sulfonimide anion paired with lithium. The backbone polarity and rigidity prevent the formation of ordered domains, resulting in a disordered morphology.

This aromatic organic scaffold features a rigid core connected by linkers and substituted with flexible side chains. The structure includes heteroatom-containing functional groups and extended conjugation. Substituent patterns and terminal groups modulate steric bulk and electronic distribution.
An ethyl 2-cyano-3-phenyl-2-propenoate analog substituted with a fluorine atom at the meta position. It is prepared using piperidine as a catalyst in the reaction of 3-fluorobenzaldehyde.
A morpholine-containing thiazole ester obtained from a trypsin-catalyzed reaction. The molecule is substituted with an ethyl ester group at the 5-position and a phenyl group at the 4-position.

A methylated polycyclic aromatic compound with a central cyclooctatetraene core. Prepared by the palladium-catalyzed dimerization of 2-iodo-4,4'-dimethyl-1,1'-biphenyl. The molecule adopts a saddle conformation due to the eight-membered ring.

A 1:1 hydrogen-bonded complex formed between 4-dodecyloxyphenylazobenzoic acid and 4-(4'-pyridylazophenyl)-4''-dodecyloxybenzoate, characterized by an extended linear assembly featuring two terminal dodecyloxy chains.
Class III glass former with a yellowish transparent color. Exhibited glass instability and crystallization under humid storage conditions.
A tetracyclic triterpene acid found in Poria cocos. It aggregates into regular nanoscale fibers, forming supramolecular gels in mixed solvents.
A rigid, paddlewheel-shaped hydrocarbon consisting of three benzene rings fused to a bicyclo[2.2.2]octatriene bridgehead system, synthesized via Diels-Alder cycloaddition of anthracene and benzyne.

Prepared via the modification of a Guerbet glucoside, this compound features a long 2-hexyldecyl tail and a peracetylated 6-bromo-6-deoxy-glucose head group. It functions as a precursor for the attachment of functional moieties.

The molecule consists of a 3,3′,4,4′-biphenyltetracarboxylic diimide core substituted at the nitrogen atoms by 4-(hexadecyloxy)phenyl groups. It features a rigid central aromatic biphenyl system fused with two imide rings, flanked by terminal phenyl rings bearing long n-hexadecyloxy alkyl chains.
A tri-hydroxy functionalized cage molecule prepared from methoxy-substituted precursors, known for forming hydrogen-bonded assemblies in the solid state.

A sulfated polysaccharide polymer composed of repeating disaccharide units consisting of alternating D-galactose and 3,6-anhydro-D-galactose residues, with a single sulfate ester group located at the C4 position of the galactose unit.

A conjugated organic polymer composed of repeating pyrrole units linked at the 2 and 5 positions. It is synthesized in this work via electrochemical deposition from a solution containing pyrrole monomer and sodium perchlorate. The material features a five-membered heterocyclic backbone containing nitrogen, known for its electrical conductivity and redox capabilities.

Prepared by the palladium-catalyzed reaction of a dibrominated azo precursor with a dioxaborolane reagent. This molecule features an azobenzene core functionalized with two pinacol boronate ester groups at the para positions.

This molecule is an ortho-fluorinated acrylanilide derivative. It exists as a solid compound. It is primarily used to investigate the influence of ortho-substitution on the mechanism of photocyclization.
Gold nanoparticles functionalized with surface ligands consisting of a cyanobiphenyl unit connected to the metal core via an undecyl chain and a sulfur atom.

This compound features a heptane spacer connecting a cyanobiphenyl group and a cyano-substituted azobenzene unit via thioether linkages. The structure exhibits extended conjugation through its aromatic rings. Terminal nitrile groups modulate the polarity and electronic distribution of the framework.

OEGMA500-DEGMA (12 mol % OEGMA500) is an aromatic organic scaffold featuring a rigid core connected by linkers and substituted with flexible side chains. The structure includes heteroatom-containing functional groups and extended conjugation, with substituent patterns defining the overall shape and polarity. Variations in ring composition and terminal groups modulate steric bulk and electronic distribution across the framework.

A di-unsaturated Schiff base ester comprising a central core of two phenyl rings linked by an imine bond. One phenyl ring is substituted with a hexyloxy group, while the other is esterified with a (9Z,12Z)-octadeca-9,12-dienoyl chain containing two cis-double bonds.

α,α'-Dihexyl-quaterthiophene features a linear backbone composed of four thiophene rings linked via carbon–carbon bonds at the α-positions (2,5-linkages), creating an extended conjugated system. This quaterthiophene framework is substituted at the terminal α-positions of the outer rings with n-hexyl groups, resulting in two hexyl chains extending from opposite ends of the molecule.
Curdlan ester derivative (m=4). Rapidly crystallized.

4'-(3-cyclopropylpropoxy)-[1,1'-biphenyl]-4-carbonitrile features a rigid biphenyl core substituted with a nitrile group and a 3-cyclopropylpropoxy ether chain. The aromatic system provides extended conjugation, while the flexible side chain and polar terminal group modulate the molecular shape and electronic nature.

The molecule consists of a chromenylium cation core substituted with a trifluoromethanesulfonate anion. The cationic core features a 6-dodecyloxy group and a 7-methoxy group attached to the chromenylium ring system. At the 2-position of the chromenylium ring, there is a phenyl ring substituted with two dodecylsulfanyl chains at the 3 and 4 positions.
A dimer molecule featuring a nonamethylene spacer and anthracene terminal groups connected via azomethine linkages.
A symmetric organic compound comprising a central benzene ring connected by azomethine linkages to two terminal phenyl rings, each bearing a pentyl alkyl group.
An acrylanilide analogue containing a five-membered cyclopentene ring fused to the amide group. It is a crystalline solid used to access cyclopenta[c]quinolin-4-ones.
Xylan ester derivative (m=10). No LC formation observed.

A benzoic acid derivative in which the hydrogen at the meta- position (position 3) has been replaced by a decanoyloxy group, comprising a ten-carbon aliphatic chain attached to the benzene ring via an ester linkage.

A synthesized monomer featuring a 3-fluoro-4-methoxyphenyl group attached to a cyanoacrylate core. The compound was prepared to investigate the effects of ring substitution on the properties of resulting styrene copolymers.

4'-((6-cyclohexylhexyl)oxy)-[1,1'-biphenyl]-4-carbonitrile is a nitrile derivative based on a rigid biphenyl core. It features a 4'-hexyloxy chain terminated by a cyclohexyl ring, providing a flexible aliphatic tail. The aromatic system is capped by a polar cyano group at the opposing position.
A cyclic poly(vinyl ether) analogue synthesized from 2,3-dihydrofuran. This polymer possesses a significantly higher softening temperature compared to its acyclic counterparts.
PROBA. Forms hydrogen bonded dimers in the crystalline state.

This aromatic scaffold comprises a rigid core connected by linkers to flexible side chains. Heteroatoms and extended conjugation are present, with substituent patterns defining shape and polarity. Ring compositions and terminal groups modulate steric bulk and electronic distribution.

A synthetic oxidized phospholipid characterized by a glycerol backbone esterified at the sn-1 position with a stearoyl chain and at the sn-2 position with an 11-hydroxyeicosatetraenoyl chain, linked to a phosphocholine headgroup at the sn-3 position.

This molecule features a central nonane chain linking two rigid azobenzene units via sulfur bridges. Each terminal aromatic system is substituted with a cyano group, creating extended conjugation. The structure integrates a flexible alkyl spacer with polar, conjugated aromatic cores.
An acetylated salicylate formed by the esterification of the phenolic hydroxyl group of salicylic acid.

A photo-responsive caged compound. Upon irradiation with light, it undergoes cleavage to release a proton and a sulfate species, effectively functioning as a photoacid generator to alter local pH or surface tension.

A symmetric molecule featuring a central terephthalohydrazide core linked via hydrazone bonds to two 3,4-bis(dodecyloxy)benzylidene groups, where each terminal phenyl ring is substituted with two dodecyloxy chains at the meta and para positions.

2O3 is an aromatic scaffold featuring a rigid core connected by linkers and substituted with flexible side chains. The structure includes heteroatom-containing groups and extended conjugation. Variations in ring composition and terminal groups modulate steric bulk and electronic distribution.

An organic semiconductor material featuring a dithienofuran core flanked by 4-isopropylphenyl groups. It is obtained by reacting a brominated alkynylfuran precursor with a sulfur source under copper catalysis.
A mono-nitro substituted rigid aromatic cage produced by electrophilic nitration of the parent hydrocarbon framework.
A C3-symmetric aromatic core consisting of a benzene ring substituted with three primary amide groups.

A symmetrical conjugated compound obtained by the condensation of terephthalaldehyde with 4-(phenyldiazenyl)aniline. It possesses an extended pi-electron system containing central imine linkages and terminal azo groups connecting aromatic rings.
A trihydroxybenzoic acid obtained from lignin depolymerization, functioning as a precursor for antioxidants and pharmaceutical hybrids.

Molecular structure: The molecule consists of a central benzene ring bearing three thiophene substituents at the 1,3,5-positions. Each substituent is a five-membered thiophene ring (containing one sulfur atom) connected to the benzene core through a carbon–carbon bond from the thiophene 2-position, giving a tris(thiophen-2-yl)benzene framework.

Synthesis: It is prepared by cyclotrimerization (trimerization) of 2-acetylthiophene under basic conditions using triethylamine, forming the 1,3,5-substituted benzene core with three thiophen-2-yl groups.
A meso-tetraarylporphyrin derivative featuring para-methyl substituents on the phenyl rings.
A diamine monomer used to prepare amorphous and soluble asymmetrical diaryl-ether-modified aramids.
An ethyl ester of orthosilicic acid consisting of a central silicon atom bonded to four ethoxy groups. It serves as a common precursor in sol-gel synthesis for generating silica networks.

An intermolecular 1:1 complex formed between 4-dodecyloxyphenylazobenzoic acid and 4-(4'-pyridylazophenyl)-4''-octyloxybenzoate, stabilized by hydrogen bonding between the carboxylic acid and pyridine moieties. The structure comprises a rod-like core with terminal dodecyloxy and octyloxy chains.
A semi-synthetic ansamycin antibiotic derived from Amycolatopsis rifamycinica. It features a macrocyclic lactam ring system bridging a naphthoquinone chromophore.

An organic azide precursor characterized by a dodecyloxy-substituted nitrobenzyl core linked to an ethyl carbonate chain. This molecule is utilized as a building block in the copper-catalyzed synthesis of functionalized amphiphiles.
A phosphonium ionic liquid derivative composed of trihexyl(tetradecyl)phosphonium cations and a hexachlorolanthanate(III) anion. The bulky phosphonium cations contain multiple long alkyl chains.
A metalloporphyrin consisting of a protoporphyrin IX macrocycle chelated with a central tin ion.
A 1,5-dibromoalkane derivative featuring a propyl chain at the 3-position. Synthesized by ring opening of 4-propyltetrahydropyran with HBr or from the corresponding diol.
A cyclopentyl rifamycin derivative. It is an ansamycin antibiotic containing a macrocyclic ring system and a piperazinyl moiety.
An organic salt formed by pairing a synthetic retinoid derivative having a benzoic acid moiety with a short-chain tertiary amine.

N-phenylmethacrylamide is a methacrylamide derivative in which one of the amino hydrogens has been substituted by a phenyl group. It is a solid compound. It has a role as a reference material and a starting material.

A fluorinated organic molecule prepared by reacting a hexyloxy-substituted azobenzoic acid with 2-(trifluoromethyl)aniline. The compound possesses a rod-like geometry with a diazo bridge and an amide connector, terminated by a sterically demanding ortho-trifluoromethyl phenyl ring.

The molecule consists of a hexadecyl aliphatic tail attached to a zwitterionic headgroup. This headgroup features a central quaternary ammonium nitrogen atom substituted with two methyl groups. The nitrogen atom is linked to a terminal sulfonate group via a linear four-carbon butyl spacer.
S-MBOBA. Pure MBOBA only shows crystalline dimers.
An anthraquinone derivative found in Rheum palmatum. It forms sustained-release hydrogels responding to temperature and pH, driven by stacking interactions of its planar core.
A meso-tetraarylporphyrin derivative containing para-hydroxy groups on the phenyl rings, used as a precursor for further functionalization.
A polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbon featuring a planar hexa-peri-hexabenzocoronene core substituted with dodecyl chains and oligo(ethylene glycol) chains in a gemini-shaped configuration.

An isopropyl ester derivative containing a diphenylphosphine oxide group linked via an E-alkene, synthesized using a copper/base catalytic system. The molecule combines a branched alkyl chain with a rigid phosphine oxide core.

N-(4-(Methylthio)phenyl)cyclohex-1-ene-1-carboxamide (S31) is an aromatic organic scaffold featuring a rigid core connected by linkers and substituted with flexible side chains. The structure includes heteroatom-containing functional groups and extended conjugation, with substituent patterns defining the overall shape and polarity. Variations in ring composition and terminal groups modulate steric bulk and electronic distribution across the framework.
A propenoate ester bearing a nitrile functionality and a phenyl ring substituted with an ethoxy group at the ortho position. The molecule is prepared through base-catalyzed condensation.

Poly(p-phenylene) is a linear aromatic polymer composed of repeating benzene rings connected to each other through carbon–carbon single bonds at the para positions, forming a continuous chain of para-linked phenyl units. It can be synthesized by direct oxidative dehydrocoupling of benzene rings to create the inter-ring C–C bonds, using either a binary reagent system in which a Lewis acid and an oxidant act together (e.g., a Lewis-acid metal chloride paired with an oxidizing metal salt) or a single reagent that serves both roles (such as an iron(III) chloride system). Alternative preparations include metal-mediated coupling routes: a Wurtz–Fittig-type coupling that joins aryl halide-derived intermediates via reactive metal species to form the para-phenylene backbone, and an Ullmann-type coupling that forms aryl–aryl C–C bonds through copper-mediated coupling of aryl halide units, yielding the same para-linked polyphenylene framework. Precursor-based approaches are also described, where a processable precursor polymer is first assembled and then chemically converted into the fully aromatic para-linked poly(p-phenylene) chain.

2O2 is an aromatic organic scaffold featuring a rigid core connected by linkers and substituted with flexible side chains. The structure includes heteroatom-containing functional groups and extended conjugation. Variations in ring composition and terminal groups modulate steric bulk and electronic distribution.
A discrete dimeric complex salt featuring two ytterbium(III) ions bridged by acetate ligands, crystallized with two 1-ethyl-3-methylimidazolium cations.
A nitrogen-containing heterocycle substituted with a single linear eighteen-carbon alkyl chain. This imidazole derivative serves as a precursor for the synthesis of dialkylated imidazolium salts.

A Schiff base ester derivative comprising a central azomethine linkage connecting two phenyl rings. One phenyl ring is substituted with a terminal hexyloxy chain, while the other is attached via an ester linkage to a pyridine ring.

The compound is 7-(dodecyloxy)-6-methoxy-2-(3,4-bis(dodecylsulfanyl)phenyl)chromenylium trifluoromethanesulfonate, featuring a flavylium core substituted with a methoxy group, a dodecyloxy chain, and a phenyl ring bearing two dodecylsulfanyl chains.
An acrylanilide derivative bearing a para-trimethylsilyl group on the N-phenyl ring. It is a solid compound synthesized for enantioselective energy transfer catalysis.

A lithium salt of a phosphinate derivative, featuring a phosphorus atom bonded to a phenyl ring, a 2,4,6-trimethylbenzoyl group, and an oxygen anion. This compound is highly water-soluble and utilized to initiate crosslinking under blue light irradiation.
Curdlan ester derivative (m=12). No LC formation observed.

A cationic gold(III) porphyrin complex comprising a meso-tetrakis(4-dodecyloxyphenyl)porphyrin core coordinated to a central gold(III) ion, balanced by a chloride counteranion. The structure features four dodecyloxy chains attached to the para-positions of the meso-phenyl rings.
The molecule consists of a dodecyl alkyl chain connected via an ether linkage to a polyethylene glycol chain containing seven repeating units.

A second-generation dendron derived from 3,5-dihydroxybenzyl alcohol. It possesses two large branches, each carrying two amino-nitro-substituted azobenzene units linked by tetra(ethylene glycol) spacers, resulting in a molecule with a total of four azobenzene groups.
A meso-tetraarylporphyrin derivative substituted with para-methoxy groups on the phenyl rings.
A thiazole derivative incorporating a pyrrolidine ring. The structure comprises a 5-methoxycarbonyl-4-phenylthiazole core with the cyclic amine attached at the 2-position.

4-hydroxy-3-nitrobenzoic acid is an aromatic organic scaffold featuring a rigid core connected by linkers and substituted with flexible side chains. The structure includes heteroatom-containing functional groups and extended conjugation, with substituent patterns defining the overall shape and polarity. Variations in ring composition and terminal groups modulate steric bulk and electronic distribution across the framework.

A heterometallic coordination species generated in alkaline solution involving a sugar acid ligand bridging calcium and iron centers. The formation depends on pH-dependent equilibria involving hydroxyl groups and the carboxylic moiety, often existing as a 1:1:1 stoichiometric species.
A propionic acid derivative featuring a phenyl ring substituted with an isobutyl group. It is a common non-steroidal anti-inflammatory agent.
A mononuclear aromatic amine substituted with two primary amino groups at the meta positions. It is commonly employed as a curing agent in the synthesis of epoxy-based thermosets.

A sterol derivative in which the hydroxyl group at the 3-position of cholesterol is esterified with sulfuric acid. It retains the tetracyclic steroid core and possesses an anionic headgroup, allowing it to stabilize colloidal dispersions.

p-Pentyloxyphenol consists of a single benzene ring bearing two para (1,4-) substituents: one phenolic hydroxyl group (–OH) directly bonded to the aromatic carbon, and one pentyloxy group (–O–CH2–CH2–CH2–CH2–CH3) where the aromatic ring is connected through an ether oxygen to a linear five-carbon alkyl chain. No step-by-step synthesis is described in the provided material; the compound is indicated as being obtained from a commercial supplier.
A triblock copolymer synthesized using 2,6-pyridinedicarboxylic acid, propylene glycol, and PEG-2000. It contains a central polyester block with 2,6-substituted pyridine rings.
A meso-tetraarylporphyrin derivative substituted with para-nitro groups on the phenyl rings.
A cationic amphiphile featuring a propane backbone linked to two unsaturated octadecenyl chains via ether bonds and a quaternary trimethylammonium headgroup.

A diketopyrrolopyrrole-based conjugated copolymer incorporating methyl-substituted bithiophene units in the backbone, where the methyl groups introduce steric hindrance between adjacent thiophene rings, resulting in a highly twisted molecular conformation.
A symmetric organic molecule based on a perylene-3,4,9,10-tetracarboxylic diimide core, functionalized at both imide nitrogen atoms with branched 1-heptyloctyl alkyl chains.
A supramolecular complex formed between a synthetic retinoid and a long-chain stearyl tertiary amine via electrostatic attraction.
A linear saturated hydrocarbon chain with twenty carbon atoms. It is often used as a core material in microencapsulation for thermal energy regulation.
A crosslinked polymer network composed of polyacrylate backbones with pendant side chains. Each side chain consists of a pentyl spacer linking the backbone to a 4'-cyanobiphenyl-4-yloxy group.

A symmetric organic molecule comprising a central thiophene ring connected via imine linkages at the 2- and 5-positions to two phenyl rings, where each phenyl ring is substituted at the para-position with a hexadecyl chain.
A meso-tetraarylporphyrin derivative bearing meta-chloro substituents on the phenyl rings.
An aromatic diacid chloride molecule consisting of two benzoyl chloride units connected by a central azo linkage in the para positions.
An organic molecule comprising a 3,3',4,4'-biphenyltetracarboxylic diimide core substituted at the N and N' positions with 4-(n-octyloxy)phenyl groups.
An acrylanilide compound substituted with a tert-butyl group at the para position of the N-phenyl ring. It is a solid material used in photochemical transformations.
A hydrophobic molecule consisting of two alpha-tocopherol units linked by a phosphate diester bond.
An aminoglycoside antibiotic complex comprising a deoxystreptamine ring linked to glucosamine and kanosamine glycosides.
A copolymer of di(ethylene glycol) methyl ether methacrylate and poly(ethylene glycol) methyl ether methacrylate. The side chains contain approximately five ethylene glycol units.

An intermolecular adduct formed between 4-decyloxyphenylazobenzoic acid and 4-(4'-pyridylazophenyl)-4''-octyloxybenzoate in a 1:1 ratio. The linear assembly is stabilized by a hydrogen bond connecting the carboxylic acid group of the first component to the pyridine nitrogen of the second, featuring terminal decyloxy and octyloxy alkyl chains.

A pentacyclic triterpene alcohol isolated from the bark of Betula papyrifera. The molecule contains a lupane skeleton with two hydroxyl groups, capable of organizing into porous, flower-like superstructures in supramolecular systems.

An ionic organic salt composed of a five-membered pyrrolidinium ring substituted with two ethyl groups, paired with a bis(fluorosulfonyl)imide anion. It is utilized as a solid electrolyte material characterized by a disordered crystal lattice that supports ionic conductivity.

A semi-synthetic taxane derivative. The chemical structure features a complex taxadiene core with multiple chiral centers, four ester groups, and a hydroxyl group at position 10. It also possesses a phenylisoserine side chain with a tert-butyl carbamate protecting group.

A benzyltetrahydroisoquinoline alkaloid isolated from plant roots. The molecular structure consists of a tetracyclic morphinan skeleton containing a tertiary amine, an alpha,beta-unsaturated ketone, a phenolic hydroxyl group, and methoxy substituents. It is characterized by its specific stereochemistry and is utilized for its immunomodulatory activities.
A conjugated copolymer consisting of alternating thiophene and quinoxaline units, where the quinoxaline core is substituted at the 2 and 3 positions with 3-octyloxyphenyl groups.

A synthetic polypeptide consisting of a peptide backbone with benzyl ester side chains. The polymer adopts an alpha-helical conformation stabilized by intramolecular hydrogen bonds and is utilized as a dielectric material in organic field-effect transistors.

PES-5 is an aromatic organic scaffold with a rigid core connected by linkers and substituted with flexible side chains. The structure includes heteroatom-containing functional groups and extended conjugation. Variations in ring composition and terminal groups modulate steric bulk and electronic distribution.
A synthetic lipid comprising an sn-glycerol backbone substituted at the 1- and 2-positions with myristoyl fatty acid chains and at the 3-position with an alpha-linked D-glucopyranosyl headgroup.

A Schiff base molecule synthesized via the condensation of 6-aminocoumarin and a pyridyl-azo salicylaldehyde derivative. It features a coumarin core linked through an imine bond to a phenol ring substituted with a pyridyl-azo moiety. The structure contains a phenolic hydroxyl group and a pyridine nitrogen, capable of coordinating with ions. It acts as a supramolecular gelator in aqueous organic solvents and exhibits optical properties responsive to specific anions and metal ions.

N-(Phenyl-d5)cyclohex-1-ene-1-carboxamide (1v) is an aromatic organic scaffold featuring a rigid core connected by linkers and substituted with flexible side chains. The structure includes heteroatom-containing functional groups and extended conjugation, with substituent patterns defining the overall shape and polarity. Variations in ring composition and terminal groups modulate steric bulk and electronic distribution across the framework.
A benzene-1,3,5-tricarboxamide core substituted with three propyl linkers, each terminating in a didodecylamino group.
A tetracyclic triterpenoid component of Poria cocos. It self-associates to yield fibrous networks and gels, sharing structural features with other fungal acids.

A palladium-metalated tetraazaporphyrin substituted with eight ethylsulfanyl groups. Synthesized to explore heavy-atom effects in conjugated macrocycles, it is structurally analogous to its nickel counterpart but contains a larger 4d transition metal.

A chemically stable n-type organic semiconductor featuring a planar perylene core flanked by two octyl-substituted imide groups. This structure facilitates electron mobility and air stability, making it suitable for application in organic phototransistors and optoelectronic devices.
A comb-like polymer with a polyacrylate backbone and sixteen-carbon alkyl side chains. Synthesized via radical polymerization, it is used in shape-stabilized composites.

A thiazole derivative prepared via a multicomponent reaction incorporating diisopropylamine. The structure includes an ethyl ester and a sterically hindered diisopropylamino group on the heteroaromatic ring.

A synthetic molecule consisting of a gentiotriose moiety attached to a 1,2-di-O-myristoyl-sn-glycerol backbone. The hydrophilic headgroup is a linear trisaccharide composed of three glucose units connected by beta 1-6 glycosidic linkages, while the hydrophobic tail comprises two myristoyl fatty acid chains esterified to the sn-1 and sn-2 positions of the glycerol.

A photo-switchable chiral molecule based on an isosorbide core substituted with two 4-methoxycinnamoyl groups. It undergoes isomerization upon irradiation and is used to induce chirality in host materials.
A bent-core molecule containing a 1,3,4-oxadiazole central unit linking two phenyl rings. It features asymmetric alkyl and alkoxy chains, specifically pentyl and dodecyloxy tails.

A symmetrical linear diol featuring a central 2,4-hexadiyne core terminated by primary hydroxyl groups. Synthesized via the copper-catalyzed oxidative coupling of propargyl alcohol. Serves as a key intermediate for the preparation of various diacetylene monomers.

Compound 9 is an aromatic organic scaffold featuring a rigid core connected by linkers and substituted with flexible side chains. The structure includes heteroatom-containing functional groups and extended conjugation. Ring composition and terminal groups modulate steric bulk and electronic distribution.
A cubic organic-inorganic perovskite compound consisting of methylammonium cations and a lead bromide lattice, exhibiting strong optical properties and applications in light-emitting diodes.
Used for calibration of the MMP instrument.

An anthradithiophene derivative substituted with fluorine atoms and bulky triethylsilylethynyl groups. The silylethynyl substituents improve solubility and solid-state packing of the rigid heteroacene core.
A conjugated copolymer comprising a backbone of alternating electron-deficient diketopyrrolopyrrole units and electron-rich quaterthiophene segments.

This molecule features a central terephthalohydrazide core linked via hydrazone bonds to two 4-(benzoyloxy)benzylidene groups. Each of the terminal benzoate moieties is substituted at the 3, 4, and 5 positions with dodecyloxy chains, resulting in a total of six peripheral alkyl tails surrounding the extended aromatic system.
A difluorinated ethyl propenoate monomer with fluorine substituents at the 2 and 4 positions of the phenyl ring. It is prepared by condensing 2,4-difluorobenzaldehyde with ethyl cyanoacetate.

The compound is a bisimine derived from 4-(2-aminoethyl)aniline, identified as N,N'-bis[4-(6-methacryloyloxyhexyloxy)benzylidene]-4-(2-aminoethyl)aniline. It can be combined with a cross-linker to form a mixture.

A monosubstituted ether derivative of tetraphenylene. Synthesized through the palladium-catalyzed cross-coupling of 2-iodobiphenyl and a methoxy-substituted iodobiphenyl. The structure features a saddle-shaped octagonal core.
Hydrophobic, dodecanethiol-coated 4.1 nm diameter spherical gold nanoparticles. Acts as a precursor for Au@L.
A fluorinated azobenzene derivative substituted with ethyl ester groups at the para positions. It serves as a synthetic intermediate for photoactive materials.

This aromatic scaffold features a rigid core connected by linkers and substituted with flexible side chains. The structure includes heteroatoms and extended conjugation, with substituent patterns defining shape and polarity. Ring composition and terminal groups modulate steric bulk and electronic distribution.
Rod-like nanoparticles composed of beta-1,4-linked glucose units featuring abundant surface hydroxyl groups.

An aromatic organic scaffold featuring a rigid core connected by linkers and substituted with flexible side chains. The structure includes heteroatom-containing functional groups and extended conjugation. Variations in ring composition and terminal groups modulate steric bulk and electronic distribution.

1'',7''-Bis{4'-[(E)-2-(4-cyanophenyl)diazenyl]phenylthio}heptane features two rigid aromatic cores linked by a flexible heptane chain. Each core contains an azo group connecting phenyl rings and is terminated by a cyano group. Sulfur atoms connect these conjugated systems to the central alkyl spacer.
An ethyl ester prodrug containing a 4,4-dimethylthiochroman ring and a pyridine ring linked by an ethynyl group.

This compound is an organic-inorganic hybrid salt consisting of three 1-dodecyl-3-methylimidazolium cations balanced by a single hexabromoterbate(III) anion. The cationic component features a positively charged imidazolium heterocycle substituted at the nitrogen positions with a methyl group and a linear twelve-carbon dodecyl chain.
