The anionic component is an octahedral coordination complex in which a central trivalent terbium ion is surrounded by six bromide ligands, forming the [TbBr6]3− species.
UOBA. Forms hydrogen bonded dimers in the crystalline state.
A chiral low-molecular-weight gelator which forms self-assembled fibers. Agglomerated fibers exhibit an opposite CD signature compared to isolated fibers.

A water-soluble aromatic polyamide polyelectrolyte prepared from isophthaloyl chloride and 4,4'-diaminobiphenyl-2,2'-disulfonic acid. The presence of meta-substituted linkages in the polymer chain induces a kinked, random coil conformation.

A water-soluble organosilicon compound synthesized via the reaction of tetraethyl orthosilicate with ethylene glycol. It consists of a central silicon atom bonded to four 2-hydroxyethoxy groups and serves as a hydrolyzable precursor for the preparation of porous silica networks in aqueous media.

A synthetic lipid comprising a glycerol backbone substituted at the sn-1 and sn-2 positions with myristoyl (C14:0) fatty acid chains, and at the sn-3 position with a beta-linked D-glucopyranosyl headgroup.

Compound 20 is an aromatic organic scaffold featuring a rigid core connected by linkers and substituted with flexible side chains. The structure includes heteroatom-containing functional groups and extended conjugation, with substituent patterns defining the overall shape and polarity. Variations in ring composition and terminal groups modulate steric bulk and electronic distribution across the framework.

A hydrogen-bonded assembly consisting of a 1:1 complex of 4-octyloxyphenylazobenzoic acid and 4-(4'-pyridylazophenyl)-4''-decyloxybenzoate, featuring an extended aromatic core connected by azo linkages and terminated by octyloxy and decyloxy alkyl chains.

An acrylate-based single-ion conducting polymer with a flexible side chain ending in a lithium sulfonimide group. The polar ester linkages in the backbone disrupt potential ordering, leading to an amorphous material structure.
This molecule comprises an eighteen-carbon unsaturated chain linked to a saturated six-membered heterocyclic piperidine ring via an ethyl amide spacer.
A branched acyclic diol synthesized by reduction of a glutarate diester derived from hexanal and malonate.
Amorphous conjugated polymer; absence of melting or crystallization peaks due to regiorandom defects.
A linear homopolymer of beta-D-glucopyranose found in the cell walls of plants. It is typically organized into nanoscale crystalline fibrils and serves as a primary structural component in biomass.

A phospholipid characterized by a glycerol backbone esterified with a stearoyl chain at the sn-1 position and a 12-hydroxyeicosatetraenoyl chain at the sn-2 position, linked to a phosphoethanolamine head group at the sn-3 position. The sn-2 fatty acid moiety features a hydroxyl group at carbon 12 and four double bonds.

An aromatic diester derived from resorcinol and acetic anhydride. Its structure features a benzene ring with two acetoxy substituents in the meta arrangement. This compound functions as an agent for transferring acetyl groups in high-temperature transesterification reactions.

This chemical structure is a meta-chlorinated acrylanilide derivative. It is obtained as a solid compound. It serves as a model substrate for investigating regioselectivity in photocyclization reactions.

A polymethoxylated flavone derivative consisting of a 4-chromenone core substituted with five methoxy groups. It is naturally found in citrus peels and features a rigid, planar benzopyrone structure linked to a phenyl ring.
A heptapeptide derivative consisting of an N-terminal L-lysine residue connected to a C-terminal hexa-L-alanine sequence, in which the N-terminus is acetylated and the C-terminus is amidated.
A symmetric dimer formed by the condensation of 1,6-bis(4-formylphenoxy)-hexane with 1-naphthylamine. Possesses bulky naphthyl terminal groups attached to a phenylene-imine core.

i-3O2 is an aromatic scaffold featuring a rigid core connected by linkers and substituted with flexible side chains. The structure includes heteroatom functional groups and extended conjugation. Its ring composition and terminal groups modulate steric bulk and electronic distribution.

A diester molecule comprising a central 2-methylbenzene-1,4-diol core linked via ester bonds to two 4-(3-(allyloxy)propoxy)benzoic acid units. The structure features a rigid three-ring aromatic system with a lateral methyl substituent on the central ring. Extending from the para positions of the outer phenyl rings are flexible propoxy spacers that terminate in allyloxy groups containing carbon-carbon double bonds.
A meso-tetraarylporphyrin derivative featuring ortho-methyl substituents on the phenyl rings.
A molecule consisting of two cycloserine moieties linked by a terephthalaldehyde bridge via Schiff base formation.

A symmetrical organic molecule featuring a central flexible poly(tetramethylene oxide) spacer chain linked via ester bonds to two rigid arms, each consisting of a phenyl ring connected to a benzothiazole moiety through an imine linkage.

A supramolecular trimeric assembly consisting of a 1-ethyl-3-methylimidazolium iodide salt complexed with two equivalents of 1-iodoperfluorooctane via halogen bonding. In this structure, the central iodide anion functions as a dual electron-donor, coordinating with the iodine atoms of the two perfluorinated chains to form a segregated arrangement.

A hexabenzylated diglycoside derivative linked to a cyclic ketal-protected glycerol. Prepared by desilylation of the corresponding silyl ether precursor, yielding a product with a free primary hydroxyl group.
A complex heterocyclic compound with a carbonate-substituted benzyl side chain. The structure includes an oxazolone ring with a quaternary center bearing a phenyl ester group.
A polymer synthesized from 2-pyrrolidone or 4-aminobutyric acid, containing a four-carbon repeating sequence.
An oxazolidinone antibacterial agent and an analogue of linezolid, featuring a thiomorpholine ring in place of the morpholine ring.

This aromatic organic scaffold features a rigid core connected by linkers and substituted with flexible side chains. It includes heteroatom-containing functional groups and extended conjugation. Variations in ring composition and terminal groups modulate steric bulk and electronic distribution.
A gold(III) porphyrin complex with octyloxy substituents, charge-balanced by a hexafluorophosphate anion.

A first-generation Fréchet-type dendron featuring a 3,5-dihydroxybenzyl alcohol core substituted with two branches. Each branch comprises a tetra(ethylene glycol) spacer terminated by an amino-nitro-substituted azobenzene group.
A polyglycerol ester comprising a diglycerol backbone linked via an ester bond to a single oleyl chain.

An atropisomeric 1,1'-binaphthyl derivative substituted with primary amine groups at the 2,2'-positions. This C2-symmetric molecule functions as a versatile chiral scaffold for ligand design in asymmetric synthesis and coordination chemistry.

Dipalmitoylphosphatidylcholine is constructed around a glycerol backbone substituted at all three hydroxyl positions. Two of these positions, specifically the sn-1 and sn-2 carbons, are esterified with palmitic acid, resulting in two long, linear C16 saturated alkyl chains. The third hydroxyl position (sn-3) is linked to a phosphate group via a phosphoester bond. This phosphate is further esterified to a choline moiety (–O–CH2–CH2–N+(CH3)3), forming a phosphocholine headgroup. The overall structure features two ester carbonyl groups, a phosphodiester linkage, and a quaternary ammonium cation, creating a zwitterionic molecule. The central carbon of the glycerol backbone is a stereogenic center.
A dimer molecule obtained from the condensation of 1,8-bis(4-formylphenoxy)-octane and aniline. The structure consists of an octamethylene chain linking two Schiff base rigid cores.

A polyene macrolide antibiotic obtained from Streptomyces nodosus. The molecule consists of a large lactone ring containing seven conjugated double bonds and a mycosamine sugar moiety. It possesses amphiphilic properties due to the presence of a hydrophobic polyene chain and a hydrophilic polyhydroxyl region.

A polyacrylate polymer featuring a pendant group attached to the backbone via a hexyl spacer. The pendant structure consists of a biphenyl core linked to the spacer by an ether oxygen, terminating in a nitrile group at the para position of the outer phenyl ring.
A bisphosphonate compound containing a central carbon atom bonded to a hydroxyl group, a primary amino-alkyl chain, and two phosphonate groups.
A phospholipid in which a glycerol backbone is esterified at the sn-1 and sn-2 positions with two palmitic acid chains, while the sn-3 position is linked to a phosphoethanolamine group.
A tricyclic lactam featuring a seven-membered ring fused to the quinolinone core. It is a solid product of the photocyclization of N-phenylcyclohept-1-ene-1-carboxamide.

This viscoelastic network is generated through the condensation of boric acid with low molecular weight hydroxy-terminated polydimethylsiloxane chains. The resulting structure consists of siloxane chains crosslinked by the boric acid residues to form the network.

Poly(3-hydroxybutyrate) is a linear aliphatic polyester built from repeating 3-hydroxybutyrate units. Each repeat contains an ester linkage in the backbone (–O–C(=O)–) connecting to a methylene segment (–CH2–) and a chiral methine carbon bearing a methyl substituent (–CH(CH3)–), giving the recurring sequence –O–CH(CH3)–CH2–C(=O)–. The polymer chain termini correspond to hydroxyl and carboxyl (or esterified) end groups depending on chain termination.

In the reported preparation, PHB is biosynthesized intracellularly by Paraburkholderia sacchari during fed-batch fermentation on a glucose-containing mineral medium under phosphate-limited conditions. After cultivation, the biomass is harvested and processed to isolate the polymer: cells are disrupted by high-pressure homogenization, non-PHB cellular components are degraded by enzymatic hydrolysis, and the intact PHB granules are recovered by washing to remove residual salts/contaminants, followed by vacuum drying to obtain purified PHB.
A benzobisthiadiazole-based diarylethene derivative functionalized with an ethyl acrylate group. The molecule exhibits axial chirality and is prepared by direct C-H activation.

Dehydrobenz[18]annulene 1 is an aromatic organic scaffold featuring a rigid core connected by linkers and substituted with flexible side chains. The structure includes heteroatom-containing functional groups and extended conjugation, with substituent patterns defining the overall shape and polarity. Variations in ring composition and terminal groups modulate steric bulk and electronic distribution across the framework.

A polysiloxane derivative featuring a polymethylmercaptpropylsiloxane backbone grafted with 4-methoxyphenyl 4-(but-3-en-1-yloxy)benzoate side groups. The structure consists of an inorganic siloxane main chain with pendant aromatic ester moieties attached through thioether linkages formed via thiol-ene chemistry.
A para-fluorinated acrylanilide derivative where a cyclohexenyl group is connected to the amide carbonyl. It is a crystalline solid prepared for photocatalytic cyclization.
A linear saturated hydrocarbon with eighteen carbon atoms. It functions as the core material in silica or polymer shells.
A molecule consisting of a twelve-carbon lauroyl chain attached to the alpha-amino group of a lysine residue, typically present as a sodium salt.

Molecular structure: The molecule has a central 1,3,5-trisubstituted benzene core bearing three identical aryl substituents. Each substituent is a carbazole unit attached through a direct carbon–carbon bond from the benzene ring to the 3-position of a 9H-carbazole framework. The carbazole nitrogen (9-position) is N-alkylated with a linear n-octyl chain, giving three peripheral N-octyl groups.

Synthesis: Prepared by a Suzuki–Miyaura cross-coupling reaction in which a 1,3,5-tribromobenzene derivative serves as the trifunctional electrophile and an N-octylcarbazole-derived boronic acid pinacol ester (functionalized at the carbazole 3-position) serves as the coupling partner. Palladium catalysis and base-mediated transmetalation enable formation of the three C(sp2)–C(sp2) bonds linking the benzene core to the three carbazolyl arms.
A synthetic fluoroquinolone antibiotic featuring a bicyclic diazaspiroheptane moiety fused to the main quinolone ring system.
An ethyl ester derivative of a cyano-substituted propenoic acid featuring a phenyl ring with a methoxy substituent at the 2-position. It serves as a monomer for copolymerization studies.

A supramolecular polymer complex formed by the non-covalent hydrogen bonding interaction between a poly(4-vinylpyridine) backbone and a photoactive 4-hydroxy-4'-dimethylaminoazobenzene dye. The structure features a flexible organic polymer chain with pyridine side groups that act as hydrogen bond acceptors for the phenolic hydroxyl group of the push-pull azobenzene chromophore. The material is synthesized by mixing the components in solution and is typically processed into amorphous solid films.

A long-chain saturated primary alcohol consisting of a linear sixteen-carbon hydrocarbon chain terminated by a hydroxyl group. It is commonly used as an opacifier, emollient, and viscosity builder in cosmetic formulations. Produced via the reduction of palmitic acid, this waxy solid exhibits amphiphilic character due to its polar head group and non-polar alkyl tail.
Glucomannan ester derivative (m=12). Completely amorphous structure.

The molecule is an organic iodide salt featuring a cationic imidazolium core. The central five-membered imidazolium ring contains two nitrogen atoms, both of which are substituted. One nitrogen atom is methylated, while the other is bonded to a phenyl ring. This phenyl ring is substituted at the para position with a dodecyloxy group, consisting of an ether linkage connecting the aromatic ring to a linear twelve-carbon alkyl chain. The counterion balancing the positive charge of the imidazolium cation is iodide.
A symmetric molecule featuring a central 1,4-phenylene ring connected via imine linkages to two outer phenyl rings, each of which is substituted at the para position with a pentyloxy chain.

A supramolecular complex formed from the 1:1 molar association of 4-[2-(pyridin-4-yl)diazenyl]-3-methylphenyl 4-decyloxybenzoate and 4-[(4-hexadecyloxyphenyl)iminomethyl]benzoic acid. The structure is stabilized by intermolecular hydrogen bonding between the carboxylic acid group of the benzoic acid derivative and the pyridine nitrogen atom of the azo ester. The resulting assembly features a five-ring aromatic core connected by azo, imine, and ester linkages, with a lateral methyl group on the central phenyl ring of the pyridine-containing component. The complex is terminated at opposite ends by hexadecyloxy and decyloxy alkyl chains.

A water-soluble azo compound featuring two amidine groups. The structure consists of a central azo linkage connecting two isopropyl groups, each terminated with an amidine hydrochloride moiety. It acts as a radical initiator for aqueous polymerizations.
A phosphatidylcholine analog featuring a palmitoyl group at the sn-1 position and a modified hydrophobic tail at the sn-2 position, which incorporates a triazole ring and a benzyl ether linkage.
Precursor synthesized via Friedel-Crafts reaction between 2-bromobenzoyl chloride and ferrocene; used to synthesize FcKetone.
A salt complex composed of a gold(III) meso-tetrakis(4-icosyloxyphenyl)porphyrin cation and a pentacyanocyclopentadienide anion.

A glutamic acid derivative incorporating a benzimidazole moiety and two octadecyl alkyl tails. This molecule acts as a supramolecular building block, capable of forming gels and coordinating with metal ions such as lanthanides to create metallogels.
A meso-tetraarylporphyrin derivative bearing meta-bromo substituents on the phenyl rings.
A symmetric dimer consisting of two terminal pyrene chromophores connected via azomethine linkages to a central 1,8-bis(phenoxy)octane flexible core.

A rod-like aromatic ester comprising two benzene rings connected by a carbonyloxy linkage, featuring a terminal octyloxy chain and a carboxylic acid group. Synthesized by the esterification of 4-hydroxybenzaldehyde with 4-octyloxybenzoyl chloride followed by permanganate oxidation, this molecule forms centrosymmetric dimers in the solid state via hydrogen bonding between the carboxyl moieties.
A sterically distorted, tris(trimethylsilyl)-substituted cage molecule synthesized via a triple cycloaddition sequence involving ynolates and silylbenzynes.
A phosphoethanolamine lipid derivative in which the glycerol backbone is esterified at the sn-1 position with stearic acid and at the sn-2 position with 11-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic acid.

A dithienofuran derivative substituted with two phenyl rings. Synthesized through a copper-catalyzed double ring closure of a functionalized furan intermediate, it adopts a herringbone packing motif in the solid state.

PFT6BT (as represented by the provided SMILES) is an aryl/heteroaryl-conjugated structure built around a fluorene-type polycyclic aromatic core bearing multiple long alkyl substituents on the aromatic framework and at the bridgehead carbon (a quaternary carbon bearing an alkyl chain and a methyl group). One aryl position of this fluorene unit is further extended through a para-connected phenylene linkage to a substituted thiophene ring that carries a linear alkyl chain. That thiophene is connected via a carbon–carbon bond to a five-membered di-aza/thiacycle (a thiadiazole-like ring, containing two nitrogens and one sulfur), which is in turn bonded to another thiophene ring bearing an additional linear alkyl substituent. 
Synthesis details are not provided in the supplied tables/captions; in general, molecules with this pattern of aryl–aryl and aryl–heteroaryl single-bond connections are commonly assembled by forming C–C bonds between prefunctionalized aromatic/heteroaromatic fragments (e.g., halogenated and organometallic coupling partners) in stepwise cross-coupling sequences, followed by any required functional-group interconversions to introduce the alkyl-substituted thiophene and thiadiazole-linked segments.
An organic compound consisting of an ethyl ester and a nitrile group on a vinyl backbone linked to a 2,3-dimethoxyphenyl ring. It is prepared by condensation of a substituted benzaldehyde.
An unsymmetrical porphyrin containing three phenyl groups and one 4-(methoxycarbonyl)phenyl group at the meso positions.

BH2-PhC4 is an aromatic organic scaffold with a rigid core, linkers, and flexible side chains. It features heteroatom functional groups and extended conjugation, with substituent patterns defining shape and polarity. Ring composition and terminal groups modulate steric bulk and electronic distribution.
A bridged alicyclic diester comprising a central bicyclo[2.2.2]octane-1,4-dicarboxylate core linked to two 4-butanoyloxyphenyl groups.
A symmetric diimide molecule constructed from a 3,3′,4,4′-biphenyltetracarboxylic diimide core, substituted at both imide nitrogen positions with 4-(n-dodecyloxy)phenyl groups.

5OCB is an aromatic organic scaffold featuring a rigid core connected by linkers and flexible side chains. The structure includes heteroatom-containing functional groups and extended conjugation. Terminal groups and ring composition modulate the steric bulk and electronic distribution.

A supramolecular complex formed by the 1:1 molar association of 4-[(4-octyloxyphenyl)iminomethyl]benzoic acid and 4-[2-(pyridin-4-yl)diazenyl]-3-methylphenyl 4-decyloxybenzoate. The structure consists of a five-ring aromatic core incorporating azo, imine, and ester linkages, with intermolecular hydrogen bonding occurring between the carboxylic acid group of the benzoic acid derivative and the pyridine nitrogen of the azo ester. The molecule features a lateral methyl substituent on the central phenyl ring of the pyridine-containing component, along with terminal octyloxy and decyloxy alkyl chains.
A symmetrical tetrapyrrole macrocycle substituted with four phenyl groups at the methine bridges, commonly synthesized via condensation of pyrrole and benzaldehyde in acidic media.
A phosphatidylethanolamine molecule having a stearoyl group at the sn-1 position and a 15-hydroxyeicosatetraenoyl group at the sn-2 position.
Xylan ester derivative (m=4). No LC formation observed.

N-(4-(4,4,5,5-Tetramethyl-1,3,2-dioxaborolan-2-yl)phenyl)cyclohex-1-ene-1-carboxamide (1h) is an aromatic organic scaffold featuring a rigid core connected by linkers and substituted with flexible side chains. description: A random copolymer consisting of a polyacrylate backbone substituted with dodecyl side chains and oligo(ethylene glycol) methyl ether side groups.
BOBA. Forms hydrogen bonded dimers in the crystalline state.

An azo-functionalized ester prepared via diazo coupling of ethyl 4-aminobenzoate with phenol. It features an azobenzene core substituted with an ethyl ester group and a hydroxyl group at para positions.
A symmetrical compound featuring a central thiophene heterocycle connected via azomethine bonds to two outer phenyl rings, each substituted with a hexadecyloxy group.

A linear perfluorinated carbon chain consisting of ten carbon atoms and twenty-one fluorine atoms, terminated by a single iodine atom. The molecule features a rigid, rod-like fluorocarbon backbone and serves as a halogen-bond donor due to the electron-accepting ability of the terminal iodine.
An isomer of aminohydroxybenzohydrazide where the amino and hydroxyl groups are situated at adjacent positions on the aromatic core.

The compound 6,7-bis(dodecyloxy)-2-(3,4-bis(dodecylsulfanyl)phenyl)chromenylium trifluoromethanesulfonate features a flavylium core substituted with two dodecyloxy chains at the 6 and 7 positions and a phenyl ring at the 2 position bearing two dodecylsulfanyl groups at the 3 and 4 positions.
The molecule consists of a central terephthalaldehyde-derived core connected via two hydrazone linkages to terminal phenyl rings, each substituted with two dodecyloxy chains at the 3 and 4 positions.
A nitroimidazooxazine compound. It comprises a bicyclic nitroimidazole core connected to a trifluoromethoxybenzyl ether group.
Rigid, rod-like particles consisting of linear polysaccharide chains of beta(1->4) linked D-glucose units with sulfate half-ester surface groups.
A meso-tetraarylporphyrin derivative featuring meta-methyl substituents on the phenyl rings.
A tetra-substituted silicon compound functionalized with four ethylamino groups. It undergoes condensation polymerization to form silicon nitride or carbide ceramics.
A hydrophobic ionic pair consisting of a synthetic retinoid anion and a dodecyl-substituted tertiary ammonium cation.

A random copolymer synthesized via RAFT polymerization containing methyl acryloyl-L-alanyl-L-phenylalanine and N,N-dimethylacrylamide. This variant includes an alanine spacer in the hydrophobic side chain to modulate folding behavior.
A dicarboxylic acid with conjugated double bonds produced by the enzymatic ring-opening of catechol or guaiacol.

A synthetic glycerophospholipid comprising two saturated myristoyl fatty acid chains attached to a glycerol backbone. The molecule features a phosphocholine headgroup and is commonly used as a key component in the preparation of liposomal formulations.
A cellulose ether derivative in which some of the hydroxyl groups on the repeating glucose units have been hydroxypropylated via reaction with propylene oxide, forming -OCH2CH(OH)CH3 substituents.
An organic molecule synthesized from pyrrolidine, benzoyl isothiocyanate, and diethyl acetylenedicarboxylate. It features a thiazole ring substituted with an ethyl ester and a pyrrolidinyl group.
A silicon-backbone high polymer substituted with methyl groups. It serves as a precursor for silicon carbide fibers via the Yajima process involving thermal rearrangement.

This asymmetric amphiphilic molecule consists of a C18 hydrophobic chain derived from stearamide and a C11 hydrophobic chain derived from undecynoate. These two distinct hydrophobic tails are separated by hydrophilic polyether spacers and connected via a central 1,2,3-triazole linkage.

4'-cyano-[1,1'-biphenyl]-4-yl 5-cyclohexylpentanoate is a carboxylic ester resulting from the formal condensation of 5-cyclohexylpentanoic acid with 4'-hydroxybiphenyl-4-carbonitrile. It features a rigid cyanobiphenyl core connected to a flexible cyclohexyl-terminated alkyl chain.

A regio-regular polythiophene derivative substituted with a branched 2-ethylhexyl group at the 3-position. The branched alkyl side chain impacts the chain packing and crystallinity of the resulting polymer film.

An electron-rich polycyclic aromatic amine containing four dimethylamino groups distributed on a tetraphenylene core. Synthesized via cyclization of the corresponding amino-substituted o-iodobiaryl. It possesses a rigid, saddle-shaped framework.

4'-((5-cyclohexylpentyl)oxy)-[1,1'-biphenyl]-4-carbonitrile is a biphenyl derivative carrying a nitrile group at position 4 and a (5-cyclohexylpentyl)oxy group at position 4'. The structure comprises a rigid aromatic core connected to a flexible alkoxy chain ending in a saturated cyclohexane ring.

A C3-symmetric benzene-1,3,5-tricarboxamide derivative functionalized with benzoic acid groups on the periphery. It is capable of self-assembling into helical supramolecular architectures via hydrogen bonding and pi-stacking interactions.
A sterically hindered diarylethene consisting of a benzobisthiadiazole bridge connecting two 2,5-dimethylthiophene rings. It serves as a prochiral substrate for asymmetric synthesis.

A modified polysaccharide consisting of a cellulose backbone where the glucose units are fully substituted with ethyl and butyl ether groups, prepared by the etherification of ethyl cellulose with 1-bromobutane.

The resulting assembly features a five-ring aromatic core connected by azo, imine, and ester linkages, with a lateral methyl substituent on the central phenyl ring of the pyridine component and terminal hexadecyloxy and octyloxy alkyl chains.

A lanthanide salt derived from a fluorinated carboxylic acid. Synthesized by reacting lanthanum oxide with trifluoroacetic acid under reflux. Used as a precursor for the thermal decomposition synthesis of fluoride nanostructures.

A discrete dimeric complex salt featuring two praseodymium(III) ions bridged by acetate ligands, crystallized with two 1-ethyl-3-methylimidazolium cations.

A meso-tetraarylporphyrin derivative substituted with ortho-nitro groups on the phenyl rings.
This cellulose derivative consists of a glucose polymer backbone where the hydroxyl groups have been fully etherified with ethyl and pentyl side chains.
A discrete dimeric complex salt featuring two thulium(III) ions bridged by acetate ligands, crystallized with two 1-ethyl-3-methylimidazolium cations.

A donor-acceptor conjugated polymer consisting of an isoindigo acceptor unit and a thiophene donor unit. It features branched 2-decyltetradecyl side chains on the isoindigo nitrogen atoms to facilitate solubility.
A discrete dimeric complex salt featuring two lanthanum(III) ions bridged by acetate ligands, crystallized with two 1,3-diethylimidazolium cations.

A conjugated copolymer consisting of diketopyrrolopyrrole cores alternating with fluorine-substituted bithiophene linkers, where the fluorine atoms engage in intramolecular non-covalent interactions with sulfur atoms to promote a planar backbone conformation.

An amphiphilic itaconate monomer consisting of a hydrophobic dodecyl tail and a hydrophilic glycerol head group containing two hydroxyl functionalities. It is capable of forming bilayer assemblies through non-covalent interactions.
An organic monomer consisting of an ethyl 2-cyanoacrylate backbone with a 2-chlorophenyl substituent. Synthesis involves the Knoevenagel reaction of 2-chlorobenzaldehyde.

A hydrogen-bonded dimer consisting of a 1:1 complex between 4-decyloxyphenylazobenzoic acid and 4-(4'-pyridylazophenyl)-4''-dodecyloxybenzoate. The molecular assembly features an extended rod-like core connected by azo and ester linkages, terminated by decyloxy and dodecyloxy alkyl chains.

A boron-dipyrromethene (BODIPY) derivative featuring a central 4,4-difluoro-4-bora-3a,4a-diaza-s-indacene core. This fluorescent monomer is utilized to covalently label polymeric structures during synthesis.

A bifunctional organic molecule comprising a benzoic acid core with a para-hexyloxy substituent terminated by an acrylate group. The carboxylic acid functionality acts as a hydrogen bond donor for supramolecular assembly, while the acrylate group permits radical polymerization.
An N-methylated phenanthridinone derivative with a trifluoromethyl substituent. It is a solid compound obtained from the photocyclization of the corresponding acrylanilide.

A lipophilic amino-alcohol derivative comprising a naphthalene ring attached to an isopropylamine moiety through an oxymethylene bridge and a 2-hydroxypropyl linker. It is synthesized by the reaction of 1-naphthol with epichlorohydrin followed by amination with isopropylamine.
An organosilicon compound featuring a carbodiimide group flanked by two trimethylsilyl moieties. It acts as a reactant in the synthesis of polysilylcarbodiimides via trans-silylation.
A widely distributed plant sterol extracted from Arisaema heterophyllum. It forms diverse morphologies like belts, sheets, or fibers depending on the solvent.

A biaryl molecule substituted with a hydroxyl group and a nitrile group at the para positions. It is synthesized via a thiol-ene photochemical sequence involving the formation of a thioether intermediate from 4-hydroxythiophenol and 4-cyanostyrene, followed by light-induced extrusion of the linker.
An oxime intermediate formed from a methoxy-substituted phenolic aldehyde, utilized in cyanide-free nitrile synthesis.

An anionic heptapeptide consisting of an N-terminal acetyl group attached to a sequence of six L-alanine residues, followed by a C-terminal L-aspartic acid residue.
A bio-based polyester synthesized from trans-hydroxy nopol and dimethyl furan-2,5-dicarboxylate. It is a semi-crystalline polymer featuring a rigid bicyclic structure in the backbone.

A steroid ester resulting from the formal condensation of the 3-hydroxy group of dihydrocholesterol with the carboxy group of 4-fluorobenzoic acid. The molecule features a cholestane backbone connected to a 4-fluorophenyl group via an ester linkage.
A bis(azomethine) derivative based on an o-tolidine core, featuring two terminal phenylene rings each substituted with an 8-hydroxyoctoxy alkyl chain.
A symmetrical azobenzene derivative in which a central diazene unit links two phenyl rings, each para-substituted with a dodecyloxy chain terminated by an acrylate group.

An amphiphilic L-glutamic acid derivative functionalized with two long octadecyl aliphatic chains. It functions as a low-molecular-weight gelator, forming self-assembled fibrillar networks in organic solvents through intermolecular hydrogen bonding.
It features a central hydrophobic polyester block containing 2,5-substituted pyridine rings and hydrophilic PEG outer blocks.
N-(Pyridin-4-ylmethyl)oleamide comprises a long unsaturated eighteen-carbon alkyl chain connected via an amide linkage to a pyridine ring substituted at the 4-position with a methylene group.

Sulfonated poly(p-phenylene terephthalamide) is a linear aromatic polyamide composed of alternating para-substituted phenylene rings and terephthaloyl units linked by amide bonds (–NH–C(=O)–). The polymer backbone consists of benzene rings connected through para-oriented amide linkages, creating an extended conjugated chain. A sulfonic acid substituent (–S(=O)2OH) is attached directly to the aromatic ring of the phenylene segment. The repeating unit structure comprises these sulfonated aryl segments alternating with terephthaloyl moieties.

An organic salt comprising a hexadecyltrimethylammonium cation electrostatically bonded to a 4-vinylbenzoate anion. The structure features a long aliphatic hexadecyl chain attached to a quaternary ammonium center, paired with an aromatic benzoate ring substituted with a polymerizable vinyl group at the para position.
A triphenylene aromatic core substituted with four hexyloxy groups and two 6-hydroxyhexyloxy chains.

A statistical copolymer prepared from di(ethylene glycol) methyl ether methacrylate and triethylene glycol methyl ether methacrylate. The incorporation of the triethylene glycol monomer modulates the thermal response.

compound_name: Poly(ethylene oxide)-Poly(acrylic acid)-Cellulose Nanocrystal Nanocomposite (65 wt%)
description: A solid nanocomposite film comprising rod-like cellulose colloidal particles dispersed within a hydrogen-bonded matrix of poly(ethylene oxide) and poly(acrylic acid). The rod-like fillers are arranged in a periodic helicoidal architecture.

A polypeptide derivative characterized by a peptide backbone with methyl ester pendants. The macromolecule forms an alpha-helical structure and exhibits high molecular ordering in thin films, serving as a gate insulator in transistor memory devices.
A gold(III) porphyrin salt consisting of a meso-tetrakis(4-hexadecyloxyphenyl)porphyrin cation coordinated to a central gold(III) ion, balanced by a tetrafluoroborate counteranion.
Curdlan ester derivative (m=2). Rapidly crystallized.

Compound 5 features a rigid aromatic core connected by linkers and substituted with flexible side chains. The structure exhibits extended conjugation and heteroatom-containing groups that define its polarity. Variations in ring composition and terminal groups adjust the steric bulk and electronic distribution.
A sixteen-carbon saturated fatty acid with a carboxylic acid functional group. It is often combined with other fatty acids in binary mixtures.
An aminoglycoside antibiotic isolated from Streptomyces griseus, featuring a streptidine moiety linked to streptose and N-methyl-L-glucosamine glycosidic units.
A fluoroquinolone antibiotic featuring a diazabicyclononyl substituent and a methoxy group on the quinolone core.
An ethylenediamine derivative possessing two 2-aminobutan-1-ol moieties. It acts as a bacteriostatic antimycobacterial agent preventing cell wall synthesis.

A complex organophosphorus compound featuring a rigid dibenzo-oxaphosphinine ring system linked to a styryl group, synthesized from a cyclic phosphine oxide precursor. The molecule contains a bulky, fused heterocyclic core.

An organic molecule featuring a central 3,3'-dimethylbiphenyl core connected to two terminal aromatic rings through azomethine linkages, where the para positions of the terminal rings are substituted with 6-hydroxyhexoxy chains.

Synthesized via condensation of o-nitrobenzaldehyde and phenylethylamine in ethanol. It is an imine derivative featuring a 2-nitrophenyl group conjugated to a carbon-nitrogen double bond, which is tethered to a phenethyl moiety.

5-hydroxy-2-nitrobenzoic acid is an aromatic organic scaffold featuring a rigid core connected by linkers and substituted with flexible side chains. The structure includes heteroatom-containing functional groups and extended conjugation, with substituent patterns defining the overall shape and polarity. Variations in ring composition and terminal groups modulate steric bulk and electronic distribution across the framework.

Synthesized via Sonogashira coupling of 1,3,6,8-tetrabromopyrene and hex-1-yne, this planar molecule features a pyrene core substituted with four hexynyl chains at the 1, 3, 6, and 8 positions, facilitating self-assembly into microstructures.

A lipopeptide consisting of a linear hexadecyl (palmitoyl) chain attached to the N-terminus of a nonapeptide sequence comprising three L-valine residues, three L-alanine residues, and three L-lysine residues. The molecule features a hydrophobic alkyl tail and a hydrophilic peptide segment containing primary amine functional groups on the lysine side chains.

A rod-rod diblock copolymer consisting of a conjugated polythiophene block substituted with chiral (3S)-3,7-dimethyloctyl side chains and a rigid helical poly(phenyl isocyanide) block bearing octyl pendants.

An acrylate-functionalized molecule comprising a diester core and a photochromic azobenzene unit with a nitro substituent. Synthesized by coupling the diazonium salt of 4-nitroaniline with a phenol derivative containing an aniline moiety.

A side-chain single-ion conducting polymer based on a polystyrene backbone. It features a long alkyl spacer connecting the backbone to a delocalized sulfonimide anion paired with a lithium cation. The structure facilitates the formation of ordered ionic layers due to the non-polar nature of the backbone.
A steroid derivative characterized by a tetracyclic cholest-5-ene core structure, functionalized with a sulfate group at the 3-beta position and possessing a hydrocarbon side chain.
A derivative of dehydroabietic acid bearing a hydroxyl group. It forms rod-like structures, with assembly driven by hydrogen bonding and pi-stacking interactions.

A symmetric-chain supramolecular complex formed from a 1:1 ratio of 4-octyloxyphenylazobenzoic acid and 4-(4'-pyridylazophenyl)-4''-octyloxybenzoate, stabilized by hydrogen bonding between the carboxylic acid and pyridine moieties and featuring identical octyloxy terminal groups on both ends of the assembly.
A meso-tetraarylporphyrin derivative bearing para-bromo substituents on the phenyl rings.

A complex thiazole derivative prepared from a glucosamine precursor. The molecule consists of a 4-phenylthiazole-5-carboxylate core linked to a carbohydrate moiety that is fully protected with bulky pivaloyl ester groups.
A tetrahydropyran derivative featuring a phenethyl side chain with a propyl group on the aromatic ring. Prepared via Negishi coupling of a zinc reagent with a chlorophenyl derivative.
A chiral triterpenic acid extracted from Terminalia arjuna. It organizes into vesicular or fibrous morphologies in aqueous environments via hydrogen bonding and hydrophobic effects.

A rod-like organic molecule featuring a polymerizable acrylate terminus, a flexible alkyl tether, a rigid aromatic ester core, and a photoresponsive azobenzene unit substituted with a cyano group. Prepared via azo coupling of 4-cyanoaniline diazonium salt.

A cationic photoresponsive salt synthesized via the diazo coupling of p-ethoxyaniline with phenol, followed by alkylation with dibromoethane and quaternization with trimethylamine. The structure consists of an azobenzene core functionalized with an ethoxy group on one ring and a trimethylammonium ethyl ether moiety on the other.
A polymer synthesized from butyl methacrylate monomers. It features a flexible butyl side chain attached to a methacrylate backbone.
A diterpenoid alcohol consisting of a cyclohexenyl ring substituted with methyl groups and a polyene chain ending in a hydroxymethyl group. It is biologically related to vitamin A.

N-Phenylcyclohept-1-ene-1-carboxamide (1n) is an aromatic organic scaffold featuring a rigid core connected by linkers and substituted with flexible side chains. The structure includes heteroatom-containing functional groups and extended conjugation, with substituent patterns defining the overall shape and polarity. Variations in ring composition and terminal groups modulate steric bulk and electronic distribution across the framework.

A fused tetracyclic organic semiconductor based on a [1]benzothieno[3,2-b][1]benzothiophene core. The aromatic scaffold is symmetrically substituted at the 2 and 7 positions with 7,7-dimethyloctyl chains, effectively presenting hexyl spacers terminated by bulky tert-butyl groups. This functionalization strategy aims to modulate molecular packing and solubility for application in field-effect transistors.
An intermolecular 1:1 hydrogen-bonded complex formed between 4-[(4-(n-hexyloxy)phenylimino)methyl]benzoic acid and 2-chloro-4-(pyridin-4-ylazo)phenyl 4-hexadecyloxybenzoate.

A cyclotriphosphazene derivative featuring six 2-(2-carboxyvinyl)phenoxy groups, synthesized by the condensation of hexakis(2-formylphenoxy)cyclotriphosphazene with malonic acid. It exists as an amorphous solid at room temperature and crystallizes at elevated temperatures.

A star-shaped pi-conjugated molecule prepared by reacting tetrabromopyrene with 1-ethynyl-4-pentylbenzene; it contains a pyrene center and four pentylphenylethynyl arms, designed for organic electronic applications.

Molecular structure: The molecule is a symmetric bis(imine) (Schiff base) built from a central para-disubstituted benzene ring bearing two exocyclic C=N double bonds at the 1- and 4-positions. Each imine carbon is part of a benzylidene fragment that connects through the imine nitrogen to a terminal phenyl ring, giving an overall tri-aromatic, linearly conjugated framework (phenyl–C=N–phenyl–N=C–phenyl in a symmetric arrangement).

Synthesis: Prepared by Schiff-base condensation of benzene-1,4-dicarbaldehyde (terephthalaldehyde) with two equivalents of aniline. The two aldehyde groups undergo nucleophilic addition by the amine nitrogens followed by dehydration to form the two C=N linkages, yielding the bis(imine) product, which is then isolated and purified (e.g., by recrystallization).

A cationic surfactant molecule comprising a branched 2-butyloctyl chain and a glucose head group modified at the 6-position with an imidazolium ring. The imidazolium carries a short PEG-like spacer terminated with an azide, enabling click chemistry.

A conjugated polymer featuring a backbone composed of cyclopenta[c]thiophene, thiophene, and 1,4-difluorophenylene units. The structure incorporates bulky o-nitrobenzyl ester side chains with dodecyloxy tails attached to the bridging carbon of the cyclopentathiophene core.
A triterpenoid acid isolated from traditional herbs like Rosa cymosa. It is capable of forming stacked layer microstructures and gels in mixed organic-aqueous solvents.

A phenoxy-substituted phenylcyanoacrylate monomer prepared for copolymerization studies. This molecule features a bulky 4-fluoro-3-phenoxy group, which distinguishes it from the methoxy-substituted analogs in the series.
A star-shaped block copolymer consisting of a three-armed poly(ethylene glycol) core, where each arm is extended by a polystyrene chain.
Acetalized cellulose derivative containing five- and eight-membered rings. Amorphous (Tg < 25 C).

trans-4-methoxyazobenzene consists of two benzene rings connected by an azo linkage (–N=N–) in the trans (E) configuration. One phenyl ring is substituted at the para position with a methoxy group (–OCH3), while the other phenyl ring is unsubstituted, giving a para-methoxyphenyl–azo–phenyl connectivity.

A representative synthesis can be carried out by forming a benzenediazonium intermediate from aniline (via diazotization) and then performing an azo-coupling electrophilic aromatic substitution with anisole, which directs coupling predominantly to the para position relative to the methoxy substituent. The resulting azo compound is then isolated and purified to afford trans-4-methoxyazobenzene.

An anhydrous coordination polymer consisting of anionic chains of gadolinium(III) centers bridged by acetate ligands in various coordination modes, with charge balance provided by 1-ethyl-3-methylimidazolium cations.

A supramolecular complex formed from a 1:1 molar ratio of 4-decyloxyphenylazobenzoic acid and 4-(4'-pyridylazophenyl)-4''-decyloxybenzoate, featuring terminal decyloxy chains symmetrically distributed around a hydrogen-bonded aromatic core.

A semi-crystalline thermoplastic polyester synthesized via polycondensation of terephthalic acid with 1,4-butanediol or by ring-opening polymerization of cyclic oligomers. The polymer backbone features rigid aromatic ester moieties linked by flexible tetramethylene chains. It organizes into a triclinic alpha-form crystal structure under standard conditions.

This organic molecule is a bis-chalcone derivative constructed from a central cyclohexanone ring. It features two 4-ethylbenzylidene groups attached at the 2 and 6 positions of the ketone via condensation with 4-ethylbenzaldehyde. The structure comprises an extended conjugated system with ethyl substituents on the terminal aromatic rings.

A polythiophene derivative functionalized with both a hexyl chain and an electron-withdrawing cyano group on the thiophene ring. Synthesized from a bromo-substituted precursor using copper cyanide, it serves as an n-type semiconductor.

A sulfonated semialicyclic oligoimide polymer synthesized via the polycondensation of 1,2,3,4-cyclopentanetetracarboxylic dianhydride and 3,3′-bis(sulfopropoxy)-4,4′-diaminobiphenyl. The structure consists of a rigid main chain backbone incorporating cyclopentane rings linked by imide groups, with hydrophilic sulfopropoxy side chains attached to the 3 and 3' positions of the biphenyl aromatic rings.

This organic compound is classified as an acrylanilide derivative, specifically featuring a bromine atom substituted at the ortho position. It is isolated as a solid material. The structure is utilized to investigate the tolerance of ortho-halogen substituents.

A non-symmetric compound comprising an anthracene unit linked via an imine group to a phenoxy-octyloxy-benzaldehyde core, synthesized by the 1:1 molar reaction of 1,8-bis(4-formylphenoxy)octane with 2-aminoanthracene.
An asymmetric heteroacene molecule featuring an octyl group attached to the 8-position of a benzothieno[3,2-b]naphtho[2,3-b]thiophene core.

An anionic phospholipid containing two saturated myristoyl chains esterified to a glycerol backbone. It possesses a phosphoglycerol headgroup and is utilized in conjunction with other lipids to form stable lipid complexes or liposomes.
A phenolic glycoside isolated from Gastrodia elata. It consists of a benzene ring and a monosaccharide, capable of gelling organic solvents like acetonitrile.

Compound 18 is an aromatic organic scaffold featuring a rigid core connected by linkers and substituted with flexible side chains. The structure includes heteroatom-containing functional groups and extended conjugation, with substituent patterns defining the overall shape and polarity. Variations in ring composition and terminal groups modulate steric bulk and electronic distribution across the framework.

A block copolymer composed of a poly(butyl methacrylate) block and a second block featuring 4-(10-methacryloxydecyloxy)-4'-pentylazobenzene repeating units, where the azobenzene moiety is attached to the methacrylate backbone through a decyl spacer and substituted with a pentyl group at the 4' position.
A gold(III) porphyrin cation with dodecyloxy substituents paired with a tetrafluoroborate anion. The amorphous solid transitions directly to an isotropic fluid.
A saponin aglycone isolated from Albizzia julibrissin. It self-associates into irregular nanoscale entities driven by its amphiphilic structure.

A rod-like conjugated system synthesized from benzene-1,4-dicarboxaldehyde and 4'-aminobiphenyl-4-carbonitrile. The molecule features a rigid core of five phenyl rings linked by imine and single bonds, terminated by polar nitrile groups.
A thioether-functionalized rigid scaffold prepared by metalation of a bromo-precursor and reaction with dimethyldisulfide, utilized as an electrophilic halogenation catalyst.

Synthesized via the protection of 2-hydroxyethyl acrylate with trimethylchlorosilane in the presence of imidazole. It is an acrylate ester monomer containing a trimethylsilyl-protected hydroxyl group connected by an ethylene spacer. This compound is utilized as a polar comonomer in coordination polymerization.
The parent unsubstituted dithieno[3,2-b:2',3'-d]furan heteroacene. Synthesized using a copper-catalyzed strategy starting from perbromofuran and a silylated alkyne.
An oleanane-type saponin extracted from Panax ginseng. It is an amphiphilic molecule that self-associates into vesicles in aqueous solutions.

This compound is a cellulose ether derivative featuring a polymeric backbone of anhydroglucose units. The structure is characterized by the substitution of hydroxyl groups with both ethyl and hexyl ether linkages, resulting in a fully etherified material.
A discrete dimeric complex salt featuring two neodymium(III) ions bridged by acetate ligands, crystallized with two 1-ethyl-3-methylimidazolium cations.
Amorphous conjugated polymer with poly(meta,meta,para-phenylene) backbone and octyl side chains; flexible chain behavior.
A semi-crystalline polyester derived from trans-hydroxy myrtenol and dimethyl furan-2,5-dicarboxylate. It contains a bicyclic terpene moiety and exhibits high thermal stability.

A hydrogen-bonded adduct consisting of 4-(4-(hexyloxyphenylimino)methyl)phenyl nicotinate and 4-octyloxybenzoic acid, featuring a non-covalent interaction between the carboxylic acid group and the pyridyl nitrogen.
A pyrazolopyrimidinone analog featuring a hydroxyethylpiperazinylsulfonyl group attached to the phenyl ring.

A perylene bisimide derivative featuring a central aromatic core with unsubstituted imide nitrogen atoms. The core is substituted at the 1, 6, 7, and 12 bay positions with four 3,4,5-tris(triethyleneglycol monomethyl ether)phenoxy groups.
A pharmacologically active triterpenoid found in Taraxacum mongolicum. It features a lupane skeleton and is observed to aggregate into rod-like or lamellar structures.

This symmetric dimer consists of two pyrene units attached to a central nonamethylene spacer through imine linkages and phenoxy groups. The molecule features a flexible alkyl core flanked by rigid, conjugated aromatic systems.

A para-substituted aromatic diester synthesized by the reaction of hydroquinone with acetic anhydride. The molecule comprises a central benzene ring bearing two acetoxy groups at opposite positions. It acts as an acetyl donor in melt polycondensation processes.

Synthesized via glycosylation of 1,2-O-cyclohexylidene-sn-glycerol with a trichloroacetimidate donor using a Lewis acid promoter. A peracetylated diglycoside derivative protected with a cyclohexylidene acetal.
A gemini surfactant salt composed of two hexadecyldimethylammonium cations linked by an ethylene spacer, with a tartrate counterion.
An organic molecule based on a dihydrooxazole-5-one scaffold. It carries a bulky isobutyl group and a phenyl ester attached to the quaternary center. Prepared via a catalytic group transfer process.
An ester derivative of vitamin A formed by the reaction of retinol with propionic acid.

A symmetrical diester formed by the reaction of hexa-2,4-diyne-1,6-diol with p-toluenesulfonyl chloride. The molecule consists of a rigid linear diyne backbone flanked by two bulky sulfonate groups. It is known to undergo topochemical polymerization in the solid state to form conjugated polymer chains.
An amphiphilic amino acid salt produced by coupling decanoyl chloride with a lactam intermediate. It features a ten-carbon hydrophobic chain linked to the alpha-nitrogen of lysine.

An alkaline coordination compound formed by the interaction of iron(III) with tartaric acid ligands in the presence of sodium hydroxide. This specific 1:3:6 stoichiometric complex serves as a powerful solvent for cellulose by forming stable soluble species with the polysaccharide hydroxyl groups.
A quaternary ammonium salt featuring a positively charged nitrogen center substituted with two methyl groups and two dodecyl alkyl chains, balanced by a bromide counterion.
An ethyl 2-cyano-3-phenyl-2-propenoate featuring a 2,6-dichlorophenyl group. It is synthesized via the piperidine-catalyzed reaction of 2,6-dichlorobenzaldehyde.
A tetrapyrrolic macrocycle consisting of a planar aromatic porphyrin core substituted at the meso-positions with four 4-icosyloxyphenyl groups, each bearing a long aliphatic chain.
A cyclic ether with an exocyclic double bond connecting to a cyclohexylethyl moiety. Formed through Wittig reaction.

An organic compound obtained from the reaction of diethylamine, benzoyl isothiocyanate, and diethyl acetylenedicarboxylate. Its structure consists of a 4-phenylthiazole core bearing an ethyl ester group and a diethylamino substituent.
A dichlorophenyl substituted ethyl propenoate with chlorine atoms at the 2 and 3 positions. It is synthesized from 2,3-dichlorobenzaldehyde and ethyl cyanoacetate.
A nitrogen-containing fused heterocyclic compound featuring pyridine rings attached to a dithienofuran core. Prepared via copper-catalyzed reaction of a dialkynylfuran precursor with sulfide.

N-(3,5-Difluorophenyl)cyclohex-1-ene-1-carboxamide (S34) is an aromatic organic scaffold featuring a rigid core connected by linkers and substituted with flexible side chains. The structure includes heteroatom-containing functional groups and extended conjugation, with substituent patterns defining the overall shape and polarity. Variations in ring composition and terminal groups modulate steric bulk and electronic distribution across the framework.

A water-soluble polymerizable monomer characterized by a methacrylate handle and a photochromic spiro-core bearing a polar sulfonate group on the indoline ring and a nitro group on the benzopyran ring. This substitution pattern allows for pH-sensitive charge modulation in aqueous polymeric systems.
A triterpenoid aglycone obtained from licorice root. It features a ketone and a carboxylic acid group, allowing it to form spherical or petal-like assemblies in various media.
A salt form consisting of an all-trans vitamin A acid derivative complexed with a saturated C18 primary amine.

A rod-shaped compound featuring a hexyloxy tail, a central azo group, and a terminal phenyl ring substituted with an ortho-nitro group, which participates in intramolecular hydrogen bonding with the amide proton.
An organic polymer featuring a polyacrylate backbone connected via an ethyl spacer to a side group consisting of a 4-methoxy-substituted azobenzene moiety, containing diazenyl functional groups.

Molecular structure: The molecule contains an N-alkylated fused polycyclic aza-aromatic core (a fused three-ring system incorporating one ring nitrogen) bearing a long linear alkyl chain on the ring nitrogen. This core is substituted through a carbon–carbon bond to a thiophene ring that also carries a linear hexyl substituent. That thiophene is further substituted with a five-membered heteroaromatic ring containing two nitrogens and one sulfur (a thiadiazole-type ring), which is connected via a carbon–carbon bond to a second thiophene ring bearing another linear hexyl substituent.

Synthesis: Specific synthetic steps and named reactions for PCT6BT are not provided in the supplied table/caption material, so a document-extracted synthesis route cannot be stated here.
An acrylanilide consisting of a cyclohex-1-ene-1-carboxylic acid core amidated with aniline. It is a solid substrate used in enantioselective photocyclization studies.

4'-(2-cyclohexylethoxy)-[1,1'-biphenyl]-4-carbonitrile features a rigid biphenyl core substituted with a carbonitrile group. A flexible 2-cyclohexylethoxy chain is attached at the 4'-position. This structure integrates an extended aromatic system with a polar terminus and an aliphatic tail.

The structure consists of a 1:1 hydrogen-bonded complex formed between 4-octyloxyphenylazobenzoic acid and 4-(4'-pyridylazophenyl)-4''-tetradecyloxybenzoate, creating a rod-like geometry through the interaction of the carboxylic acid group and the pyridyl moiety.
An ethyl 2-cyanoacrylate analogue substituted with a 3,4,5-trimethoxyphenyl ring. This compound is prepared by Knoevenagel condensation and characterized by NMR and IR.
A hydroxyphenyl propene monomer. It is an allyl chain-substituted guaiacol extracted from clove oil.
A prostaglandin E1 analogue comprising a cyclopentanone ring substituted with hydroxy and carboxyalkyl chains.

Synthesized from terephthalaldehyde and 4-dodecyloxybenzohydrazide. The structure consists of a central phenyl ring connected by hydrazone bonds to two phenyl rings, each with a single para-dodecyloxy substituent.
A methylated dicarboxylic acid formed by the cleavage of o-cresol, serving as a potential monomer for polymers.

A substituted polysaccharide derivative of hydroxypropyl cellulose in which the hydroxyl groups of the hydroxypropyl side chains are functionalized with propionate esters and 3,5-bis(trifluoromethyl)phenyl carbamate moieties.

A porous silica nanomaterial functionalized with N-methylaminopropylsilyl moieties. Synthesized by condensing tetraethylorthosilicate in the presence of a quaternary ammonium surfactant, followed by ion exchange with the secondary amine-containing silane. The structure features a high surface area silicate framework decorated with methylamino groups.
An aliphatic polymer formed by the ring-opening polymerization of caprolactam or polycondensation of 6-aminocaproic acid.

This compound consists of a rigid aromatic core connected by linkers and substituted with flexible side chains. The framework includes heteroatom-containing functional groups and extended conjugation. Variations in ring composition and terminal groups modulate the steric bulk and electronic distribution.
A bulky organic molecule featuring a benzyloxy-substituted benzyl group attached to a dihydrooxazole core. It contains a quaternary carbon center and is synthesized via rearrangement catalysis.
A discrete dimeric complex salt featuring two erbium(III) ions bridged by acetate ligands, crystallized with two 1-ethyl-3-methylimidazolium cations.
A discrete dimeric complex salt featuring two terbium(III) ions bridged by acetate ligands, crystallized with two 1-ethyl-3-methylimidazolium cations.
An aniline derivative substituted with a hydrophobic octyl chain at the para position. It serves as an oil phase component in droplet systems and can participate in interfacial reactions.
A meso-tetraarylporphyrin derivative substituted with meta-amino groups on the phenyl rings.
A five-membered heterocyclic derivative bearing an isopropyl group and a phenoxycarbonyl moiety at the quaternary position. It serves as a product of an enantioselective rearrangement.
An ion pair comprising a gold(III) porphyrin cation with octyloxy chains and a planar pentacyanocyclopentadienide anion.

A synthetic benzoxazinone derivative bearing a trifluoromethyl group and a cyclopropylethynyl substituent. This heterocyclic compound is utilized as a non-nucleoside reverse transcriptase inhibitor in the treatment of HIV.

A donor-substituted pyrene derivative obtained from the reaction of tetrabromopyrene with 4-ethynyl-N,N-dioctylaniline, characterized by four electron-rich dioctylaminophenyl-ethynyl branches attached to the central core.
Xylan ester derivative (m=12). No LC formation observed.
Synthesized by reacting a diphenol diacetylene derivative with dodecyl bromide. The molecule features a rigid diphenyl-diacetylene core substituted with one dodecyloxy chain and one hydroxyl group.
A highly substituted phenyl propenoate featuring three methoxy groups at the 2, 4, and 5 positions of the aromatic ring. It contains a nitrile group adjacent to the ester functionality.
A phosphatidylcholine lipid featuring a glycerol backbone esterified at the sn-1 and sn-2 positions with two 12-carbon saturated lauroyl chains, linked to a phosphocholine group at the sn-3 position.

A supramolecular assembly formed via intermolecular hydrogen bonding between 4-(4-(hexyloxyphenylimino)methyl)phenyl nicotinate and 4-hexyloxybenzoic acid in a 1:1 molar ratio. The assembly consists of a pyridine-based ester derivative featuring a central Schiff base core, a terminal hexyloxy chain, and a pyridine ring acting as a proton acceptor, associated with a proton-donating benzoic acid moiety substituted with a six-carbon alkoxy tail.

Lithium (octadecylsulfonyl)(trifluoromethanesulfonyl)imide is an organic lithium salt. It features a lithium cation and a sulfonimide anion, where the central nitrogen atom is bonded to a trifluoromethanesulfonyl group and a long octadecylsulfonyl chain.
A diester molecule featuring a central 2-chloro-1,4-phenylene core connected to two 4-((6-(acryloyloxy)hexyl)oxy)benzoate groups.

2-hydroxy-4-nitrobenzoic acid is a hydroxybenzoic acid derivative. It consists of a benzoic acid core substituted with a hydroxy group at position 2 and a nitro group at position 4. The molecule features a rigid aromatic ring decorated with oxygen- and nitrogen-containing functional groups.

The molecule comprises a central biphenyl core fused with two imide rings to form a 3,3′,4,4′-biphenyltetracarboxylic diimide scaffold. The nitrogen atoms of the imide rings are substituted with 4-n-octylphenyl groups.
A biphenyl derivative synthesized from 4-cyano-4'-hydroxybiphenyl and 6-bromo-1-hexanol. It features a cyano group at one end and a hydroxylated alkyl chain at the other.

A naturally occurring iridoid derivative featuring a fused dihydropyran and cyclopentane ring system with an ester functionality. It is widely employed as a biocompatible cross-linking agent for proteins and polysaccharides such as chitosan and gelatin in the formation of hydrogels.
A heterocyclic aromatic organic compound characterized by a pyrazole ring substituted with two phenyl groups at the 1 and 5 positions.
Amorphous conjugated polymer with poly(meta,meta,para-phenylene) backbone and hexyl side chains; flexible chain behavior.

A Schiff base ester comprising a central imine linkage connecting two phenyl rings. The structure features a hexyloxy chain attached to one phenyl ring and a saturated hexadecanoyl ester chain attached to the other, forming a rod-like core with flexible alkyl tails.

A functionalized amide derivative synthesized by the reaction of alpha-bromoisobutyryl bromide with diethanolamine in dichloromethane. The molecule features a tertiary alkyl bromide moiety capable of initiating radical polymerization and two hydrophilic hydroxyethyl groups attached to the amide nitrogen.

This aromatic scaffold features a rigid core connected by linkers and substituted with flexible side chains. The structure includes heteroatom-containing groups and extended conjugation. Variations in ring composition and terminal groups modulate steric bulk and electronic distribution.

A chiral three-ring ester comprising a 4'-pentanoylbiphenyl-4-carboxylate core linked to a 4-((1-(pentyloxy)-1-oxopropan-2-yloxy)carbonyl)phenyl group. The molecule features a pentyl lactate terminal moiety, a butyl ketone functionality attached to the biphenyl system, and multiple ester linkages connecting the aromatic rings.

BH2-PhOC8 is an aromatic organic scaffold featuring a rigid core connected by linkers and substituted with flexible side chains. The structure includes heteroatom-containing functional groups and extended conjugation. Ring composition and terminal groups modulate steric bulk and electronic distribution.

Choline decanoate (1:2 molar ratio) is a three-component ionic assembly consisting of a choline cation and two decanoate-derived species: one decanoate carboxylate anion (a linear C10 alkyl chain terminating in a carboxylate group) and one neutral decanoic acid molecule (the corresponding carboxylic acid). The choline fragment is a quaternary ammonium center bearing three methyl substituents and a 2-hydroxyethyl substituent (trimethyl(2-hydroxyethyl)ammonium).

It was prepared by neutralizing choline bicarbonate with decanoic acid (salt metathesis/acid–base reaction), where carbon dioxide evolution indicates reaction progress, forming the choline decanoate ion pair. To obtain the 1:2 composition, an additional equivalent of decanoic acid was added after the initial neutralization to incorporate a second, protonated decanoic acid component. The reaction was carried out in an alcohol/water medium with dropwise addition of the fatty acid solution, followed by removal of solvent to isolate the dried formulation.

A glycerophospholipid in which the sn-1 position is acylated by a saturated stearoyl chain, while the sn-2 position is esterified with 5-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic acid (5-HETE), an oxidized derivative of arachidonic acid. The molecule features a phosphoethanolamine headgroup attached at the sn-3 position.

4'-(3-cyclohexylpropoxy)-[1,1'-biphenyl]-4-carbonitrile features a rigid biphenyl core substituted with a cyano group and a flexible 3-cyclohexylpropoxy chain. The molecule combines extended aromatic conjugation with a saturated terminal ring linked via an ether oxygen.
A hydroxylated diterpene acid derived from pine species. It aggregates into spherical nanostructures driven by non-covalent interactions.
A polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbon derivative consisting of a pyrene core substituted with four carboxylic acid groups at the 1, 3, 6, and 8 positions.

An acylphosphine oxide derivative featuring a central phosphorus atom bonded to two phenyl rings and one 2,4,6-trimethylbenzoyl group. It serves as an efficient radical generator for polymerization upon exposure to ultraviolet or visible light.
An organophosphorus compound consisting of a phosphate group esterified to a twelve-carbon alkyl chain.

A fibrous protein polymer characterized by a primary structure rich in glycine, alanine, and serine residues. In the solid state, it adopts a beta-pleated sheet configuration stabilized by hydrogen bonds, while in concentrated salt solutions, it forms ion-rich hydration layers.

The molecule is a symmetric diester centered on a 1,3-disubstituted phenylene ring. Two identical 4'-substituted biphenyl-4-carboxylate groups are attached to the central ring via ester linkages at the meta positions. The terminal phenyl ring of each biphenyl arm features a para-positioned ether substituent consisting of a (2S,3S)-2,3-difluorooctyloxy chain. This side chain introduces two stereogenic centers and two fluorine atoms on each arm, resulting in a structure defined as 1,3-phenylene bis(4'-((2S,3S)-2,3-difluorooctyloxy)biphenyl-4-carboxylate).

4'-((4-cyclohexylbutyl)oxy)-[1,1'-biphenyl]-4-carbonitrile is a biphenyl derivative with a cyano group and a (4-cyclohexylbutyl)oxy substituent. It combines a rigid aromatic core with a flexible aliphatic tail terminating in a cyclohexane ring. The linear framework supports extended conjugation.

A fluorinated copolymer synthesized from vinylidene fluoride and hexafluoropropylene monomers, featuring a semi-crystalline structure known for its mechanical flexibility and solubility in organic solvents.

This compound comprises two 4-[(4-cyanophenyl)diazenyl]phenylthio groups linked by a central undecane chain. The structure features extended conjugation through azo-linked aromatic rings terminated by cyano groups. A flexible alkyl spacer connects these rigid, polarizable moieties.

A C3-symmetric molecule based on a hexadehydrotribenzo[12]annulene scaffold substituted with three butyramide groups. It possesses a planar pi-conjugated core and amide functionalities, forming crystalline structures stabilized by intermolecular hydrogen bonds and pi-stacking interactions.
A synthetic cyclic octapeptide containing a disulfide bridge and D-amino acids.

A coordination compound consisting of a central europium(III) ion coordinated by three unsymmetrical 1-(4-(octyloxy)phenyl)-3-phenylpropane-1,3-dionato ligands and one water molecule. Each beta-diketonate ligand features a 1,3-dione core substituted with a phenyl ring at one position and a 4-(octyloxy)phenyl group at the other, incorporating an eight-carbon alkoxy chain in the para position.
A symmetric organic dimer synthesized from 1,9-bis(4-formylphenoxy)-nonane and aniline. Characterized by a nonamethylene flexible spacer and terminal phenyl rings linked via azomethine groups.

The compound is a flavylium (chromenylium) salt comprising a benzopyrylium cation and a trifluoromethanesulfonate (triflate) anion. The cationic core features a fused benzene ring substituted with a dodecyloxy group and a methoxy group. At the 2-position of the chromenylium ring, a phenyl group is attached, which is para-substituted with a dodecylsulfanyl (–S–C12H25) moiety.
A sphingosine analogue consisting of a phenyl ring substituted with a long alkyl chain and a head group containing an amine and two hydroxymethyl moieties.

A C3-symmetric organic molecule based on a triazatruxene core substituted with ethyl chains on the nitrogen atoms. It is functionalized at the 2, 7, and 12 positions with 1-hydroxy-3-(4-methoxyphenyl)prop-2-yn-1-yl arms. The synthesis involves the reaction of 2,7,12-triformyl-5,10,15-triethyl-10,15-dihydro-5H-diindolo[3,2-a:3',2'-c]carbazole with the lithium acetylide of 4-ethynylanisole, creating chiral carbinol linkages.

A regioregular polythiophene derivative where the backbone bears 5-hexylthiophene pendants directly attached to the 3-position. Prepared using Stille coupling, the structure aims to broaden absorption through conjugated side chains without vinylene linkers.
Amorphous conjugated polymer; absence of melting or crystallization peaks due to regiorandom defects.
A lanthanum salt comprising tetrabutylphosphonium cations and a hexachlorolanthanate(III) anion. The cation consists of a phosphorus atom symmetrically substituted with four butyl groups.
The compound consists of a 3,3',4,4'-biphenyltetracarboxylic diimide core substituted at the nitrogen atoms with 4-n-tetradecylphenyl groups.

A63 is an aromatic organic scaffold featuring a rigid core connected by linkers and substituted with flexible side chains. The structure includes heteroatom-containing functional groups and extended conjugation, with substituent patterns defining the overall shape and polarity. Variations in ring composition and terminal groups modulate steric bulk and electronic distribution across the framework.
A diglyceride consisting of a glycerol core esterified with two unsaturated oleic acid chains, leaving one hydroxyl group unfunctionalized.

An isopropyl phenylcyanoacrylate monomer prepared via Knoevenagel condensation involving 2-fluoro-4-methoxybenzaldehyde. The molecule contains a cyano group and an ester functionality on the vinyl moiety, designed for radical copolymerization studies.

A zinc metalloporphyrin comprising a central zinc ion and four 4-(hexyloxycarbonyl)phenyl groups at the meso positions. Prepared via the reaction of 5,10,15,20-tetrakis(4-carboxyphenyl)porphyrin derivatives with zinc acetate. The linear hexyl chains facilitate molecular self-assembly in thin films.
An ionic molecule consisting of a 1-[4-(dodecyloxy)phenyl]-3-methyl-1H-imidazol-3-ium cation and a trifluoromethanesulfonate anion.

An organosilane coupling agent consisting of a central silicon atom bonded to three ethoxy groups and a propyl chain terminated by a primary amine. It is commonly used to functionalize silica surfaces or incorporated into silica networks via condensation. The amine group facilitates further chemical modification, such as the attachment of fluorescent dyes.
A sterically hindered poly(vinyl ether) synthesized from tert-butyl vinyl ether. The bulky side group contributes to a distinct thermal profile relative to linear analogues.
A di-nitro substituted rigid paddlewheel-shaped molecule obtained by controlled nitration, utilized as a precursor for amino-functionalized derivatives.

A functionalized acrylate derivative featuring a diethoxyphosphoryl group at the beta position, synthesized via copper-catalyzed addition of diethyl phosphite to methyl propiolate. It contains both phosphonate and carboxylate ester functionalities linked by a trans-double bond.

An asymmetric organic molecule featuring a central V-shaped resorcinol core substituted with two different ester arms. One arm terminates in a dodecyloxy chain, while the other contains a triphenylene unit linked through a dodecyl spacer. Synthesized via stepwise esterification to combine rod-like and disk-like structural elements.

A symmetrical aromatic ester synthesized from phloroglucinol and acetic anhydride using a zinc acetate catalyst. The molecule consists of a benzene core substituted with three acetoxy groups at the 1, 3, and 5 positions. It serves as an acetylation reagent capable of transferring acetyl groups to phenols at elevated temperatures.

The molecule is an aromatic ester comprising a 4-hexyloxybenzoate moiety linked via a carboxylate group to a 2-chloro-4-(pyridin-4-ylazo)phenyl unit. The benzoate section features a linear hexyloxy chain at the para position relative to the ester bond. The phenolic component consists of a phenyl ring substituted with a chlorine atom and an azo group (–N=N–), which connects to the 4-position of a pyridine ring, forming an extended conjugated aryl–azo–pyridine system.

An eighteen-carbon primary alcohol in which the hydrocarbon chain is perfluorinated except for the methylene group adjacent to the hydroxyl function. This amphiphilic molecule is characterized by a bulky, stiff hydrophobic segment and exhibits a tendency to aggregate into ordered solid-like domains on water surfaces.
A nickel metalloporphyrin substituted with chiral 3,5-bis(2-methylbutoxy)phenyl groups at the meso positions, featuring a twisted geometry.
A bis-imide compound comprising a central 3,3',4,4'-biphenyltetracarboxylic diimide core substituted at the nitrogen atoms with 4-n-dodecylphenyl groups.

A fluorinated ether solvent characterized by a nonafluorobutyl chain linked to an ethyl group. It is a dense, immiscible fluid used to create distinct oil phases in aqueous environments for studying droplet interactions.

N-(4-Bromophenyl)cyclohex-1-ene-1-carboxamide (S29) is an aromatic organic scaffold featuring a rigid core connected by linkers and substituted with flexible side chains. The structure includes heteroatom-containing functional groups and extended conjugation, with substituent patterns defining the overall shape and polarity. Variations in ring composition and terminal groups modulate steric bulk and electronic distribution across the framework.

TX405-Br is an aromatic organic scaffold with a rigid core connected by linkers and bearing flexible side chains. It features heteroatom-containing groups and extended conjugation, with substituents defining shape and polarity. Ring composition and terminal groups modulate steric bulk and electronic distribution.

A metalloporphyrin complex consisting of a gallium(III) ion coordinated to a protoporphyrin IX macrocycle. The porphyrin ring is substituted with four methyl, two vinyl, and two propionic acid groups. It is utilized as a photosensitizer and an iron analogue in biological systems.
A sterically hindered porphyrin derivative bearing four 3,5-di-tert-butyl-4-hydroxyphenyl substituents, designed to prevent aggregation and used in surface assembly studies.

An elastomeric polymer network synthesized via thiol-Michael addition of a rod-like diacrylate monomer containing a central methyl-substituted hydroquinone core and pentaerythritol tetra(3-mercaptopropionate). The structure features rigid aromatic units linked by flexible aliphatic spacers and thioether crosslinks.
A meso-tetraarylporphyrin derivative bearing para-chloro substituents on the phenyl rings.

A cyclic ester comprising a five-membered dihydrofuran-2-one ring substituted with a methyl group at the gamma position. It functions as a biomass-derived platform chemical and organic solvent, typically synthesized via the catalytic hydrogenation of levulinic acid.

PES-5S is an aromatic organic scaffold featuring a rigid core connected by linkers and substituted with flexible side chains. The structure includes heteroatom-containing functional groups and extended conjugation. Ring composition and terminal groups modulate steric bulk, shape, and electronic distribution.

A hydrophilic polymer derivative consisting of high-aspect-ratio, rod-like nanoparticles derived from native cellulose. The backbone comprises beta-1,4-linked D-glucose units where hydroxyl groups are partially substituted with carboxymethyl moieties. These surface anionic groups facilitate dispersion in water, and the material is characterized by its high crystallinity and rigid structural integrity typical of polysaccharide whiskers.

A polymer consisting of a methacrylate backbone with side chains containing a phenyl benzoate core. The core is substituted with a pentyl group at one end and connected to the polymer backbone via a hexyloxy spacer at the other. It is synthesized via free radical polymerization.

N-(4-Methoxyphenyl)cyclohex-1-ene-1-carboxamide (1l) is an aromatic organic scaffold featuring a rigid core connected by linkers and substituted with flexible side chains. The structure includes heteroatom-containing functional groups and extended conjugation, with substituent patterns defining the overall shape and polarity. Variations in ring composition and terminal groups modulate steric bulk and electronic distribution across the framework.
An ethyl-substituted dihydroxybenzene synthesized from 4-ethylphenol via tyrosinase activity.
A naturally occurring dipeptide formed by the condensation of beta-alanine and L-histidine. The molecule features an imidazole heterocycle, a free carboxylic acid, and an amide linkage.

Compound 19 is an aromatic organic scaffold featuring a rigid core connected by linkers and substituted with flexible side chains. The structure includes heteroatom-containing functional groups and extended conjugation, with substituent patterns defining the overall shape and polarity. Variations in ring composition and terminal groups modulate steric bulk and electronic distribution across the framework.

An anionic saturated phospholipid in which a glycerol backbone is esterified at the sn-1 and sn-2 positions by two stearic acid moieties, while the sn-3 position is linked via a phosphodiester bond to a second glycerol molecule.

The chemical structure consists of linear chains of beta-1,4-linked D-glucose units forming rigid, rod-shaped nanoparticles with high aspect ratios. These structures feature surface hydroxyl groups and sulfate ester moieties.
A cerium(III) complex salt featuring 1-decyl-3-methylimidazolium cations and a hexabromocerate anion. The cation possesses a ten-carbon alkyl chain.

A photochromic organic molecule consisting of an azobenzene core substituted with four carboxylic acid groups at the meta positions. It is capable of forming supramolecular networks on graphite surfaces through intermolecular hydrogen bonding and exhibits reversible trans-cis isomerization under UV and visible light.
A lipidated tetrapeptide consisting of an N-terminal dodecyl (lauroyl) chain amide-linked to a linear sequence of four amino acids: L-valine, L-glutamic acid, L-valine, and L-glutamic acid.
A tetrahydropyran ring featuring an exocyclic double bond to a propyl group. Synthesized via Wittig olefination of tetrahydro-4H-pyran-4-one.
A bio-based aliphatic polyamide derived from 11-aminoundecanoic acid.

Vismodegib is an aromatic, heteroaryl carboxamide composed of a substituted pyridine ring bearing a methyl group and two additional substituents: (i) a biaryl linkage to a phenyl ring that carries a methylsulfonyl group (–SO2CH3), and (ii) a carboxamide group (–C(=O)–NH–) connecting the pyridine to a trichlorinated phenyl ring.
