A plausible synthesis assembles these connections by first forming the amide bond via coupling of a pyridine-carboxylic acid derivative (commonly activated as an acid chloride or equivalent) with a trichloroaniline to give the pyridine carboxamide. The remaining aryl–aryl bond can then be introduced using a palladium-catalyzed cross-coupling (e.g., Suzuki-type) between a halogenated pyridine intermediate and an appropriately substituted phenyl boron/organometallic partner that already bears the methylsulfonyl substituent (or by installing the methylsulfonyl group on the phenyl ring prior to the cross-coupling).

Itraconazole features a substituted triazolinone core, characterized by a five-membered heterocycle containing three nitrogen atoms and one carbonyl group. This core bears an alkyl substituent on the ring carbon and an N-alkyl substituent on the lactam-like ring nitrogen. A second ring nitrogen is bonded to a phenyl ring, which is further substituted by a tethered bicyclic urea/lactam motif incorporating two nitrogens and a carbonyl within a saturated ring. One of the nitrogens in this bicyclic unit is bonded to a chlorinated benzene ring, and that benzene also carries a benzylic methylene–oxygen linkage back to a stereogenic carbon in the bicyclic system, creating a fused N,O-containing polycyclic substructure.

A cellulose derivative in which the anhydroglucose units of an ethyl cellulose backbone are modified such that all remaining hydroxyl groups are substituted with propyl ether linkages, resulting in a fully etherified polymer containing both ethyl and propyl ether substituents.

An axially chiral diarylethene derivative featuring a benzobisthiadiazole core and a phenyl acrylate group attached to one of the dimethylthiophene units, synthesized via palladium-catalyzed C-H olefination.

A hexasubstituted cyclotriphosphazene core bearing six 2-formylphenoxy groups. It is prepared via the nucleophilic substitution of hexachlorocyclotriphosphazene with salicylaldehyde and serves as a multifunctional aldehydic intermediate for further functionalization.

cis-4-Methoxyazobenzene consists of two phenyl rings linked by an azo (N=N) double bond, with a methoxy substituent (–OCH3) on one ring at the para position relative to the azo linkage; the molecule is in the cis (Z) configuration about the N=N bond, placing the two aryl groups on the same side of the azo unit. A typical synthesis forms the azobenzene framework by diazotizing p-anisidine to generate the corresponding arenediazonium intermediate, followed by electrophilic azo coupling with aniline (or another phenyl nucleophile) to yield 4-methoxyazobenzene; the cis isomer can then be obtained by photoisomerization of the E (trans) azobenzene to the Z (cis) form.

A synthetic lipopeptide comprising a palmitoyl aliphatic tail conjugated to the N-terminus of a peptide sequence consisting of three valine, three alanine, and three glutamic acid residues. The molecule features a hydrophobic alkyl chain and a hydrophilic C-terminal domain with three carboxylic acid groups.

A sterically hindered ester derivative incorporating a diphenylphosphine oxide functionality, synthesized via copper-catalyzed hydrophosphorylation. The tert-butyl group provides bulkiness to the ester end of the conjugated system.

A 1:1 supramolecular assembly formed via hydrogen bonding between the carboxylic acid moiety of 4-decyloxyphenylazobenzoic acid and the pyridine moiety of 4-(4'-pyridylazophenyl)-4''-tetradecyloxybenzoate, featuring decyloxy and tetradecyloxy substituents on the respective components.

PECH75 is an aromatic organic scaffold featuring a rigid core connected by linkers and substituted with flexible side chains. The structure includes heteroatom-containing functional groups and extended conjugation. Ring composition and terminal groups modulate steric bulk and electronic distribution.

A conjugated polymer based on an isoindigo-bithiophene backbone with branched aliphatic side chains. It forms aggregates in various solvents that influence the morphology and electronic performance in organic field-effect transistors. The structure includes alkyl substituents to promote solubility and ordering.
A meso-tetraarylporphyrin derivative substituted with ortho-methoxy groups on the phenyl rings.
A pyrrolopyrimidinone core bearing a hydroxyethylpiperazinylsulfonylphenyl group and a propoxy ether.

The compound is a 1:1 supramolecular complex formed via hydrogen bonding between the carboxylic acid group of 4-dodecyloxyphenylazobenzoic acid and the pyridine nitrogen of 4-(4'-pyridylazophenyl)-4''-tetradecyloxybenzoate, featuring terminal dodecyl and tetradecyl alkoxy chains.

A phenylpropanoid consisting of a phenol ring substituted with a para-hydroxyl group and a propenoic acid side chain. It is synthesized biologically via the shikimate pathway, specifically through the non-oxidative deamination of tyrosine by tyrosine ammonia-lyase. This compound contains carboxylic acid and phenolic functional groups and serves as a monomer for the synthesis of biodegradable high-performance thermoplastics.

PET-5S is an aromatic organic scaffold featuring a rigid core connected by linkers and substituted with flexible side chains. The structure includes heteroatom-containing functional groups and extended conjugation. Ring composition and terminal groups modulate steric bulk and electronic distribution.

A vinylphosphine oxide derivative featuring a styryl group attached to a diphenylphosphorus center, synthesized from phenylacetylene and diphenylphosphine oxide. It is a conjugated system with extended pi-delocalization across the aromatic rings and the double bond.

This molecule is an ester-functionalized acrylanilide derivative which incorporates a methyl benzoate moiety. It exists as a solid substrate. The compound is utilized in studies to demonstrate functional group tolerance.

A thiazole-based ester formed by the condensation of N-benzylmethylamine, benzoyl isothiocyanate, and diethyl acetylenedicarboxylate. It features an ethyl ester and a benzyl(methyl)amino group on the heterocyclic core.
An organic ester characterized by a 2,3,4-trimethoxyphenyl ring attached to a cyano-substituted vinyl group. It is used as a starting material for copolymerization.

A rod-like aromatic azo compound consisting of two phenyl rings linked by a diazene bridge in an E-configuration. One phenyl ring is para-substituted with a carboxylic acid group, while the other bears a para-allyloxy tail containing a terminal alkene.

A stiff, rod-like nanomaterial comprising highly ordered crystalline domains of linear polysaccharide chains formed from beta-1,4-linked D-glucose units. The surface features numerous hydroxyl groups allowing for extensive chemical functionalization.
Gold nanoparticles surface-functionalized with 4'-((8-mercaptooctyl)oxy)-4-cyanobiphenyl ligands, which consist of a biphenyl carbonitrile moiety tethered by an octyl chain ending in a thiol group.
A synthetic phospholipid composed of a phosphatidylcholine headgroup, a standard saturated fatty acid chain, and a hydrophobic tail containing a triazole ring linked to a nitrobenzyl carbonate group.

An organic salt consisting of a five-membered heteroaromatic cation substituted with ethyl and methyl groups, paired with an iodide anion. It serves as the ionic component in the synthesis of halogen-bonded complexes.

An unsymmetrical organic dimer consisting of a 4-cyanobiphenyl group and a 4-(trans-4-ethylcyclohexyl)-2',3-difluorobiphenyl unit connected by an undecamethylene dioxy chain. The molecule is characterized by a central flexible spacer, lateral fluorine substitution on one of the aromatic cores, and a terminal cyano group.

Compound 15 is an aromatic organic scaffold featuring a rigid core connected by linkers and substituted with flexible side chains. The structure includes heteroatom-containing functional groups and extended conjugation, with substituent patterns defining the overall shape and polarity. Variations in ring composition and terminal groups modulate steric bulk and electronic distribution across the framework.

A rod-like aromatic diester consisting of two phenyl rings linked by a single bond, with acetoxy groups at the para positions of the biphenyl core. Synthesized from (1,1'-biphenyl)-4,4'-diol and acetic anhydride, this compound is utilized as an intermediate and acetylating additive in polymerization reactions.

This compound consists of an o-tolidine core substituted with two 4-(10-hydroxydecoxy)benzylidene groups at the nitrogen atoms. The structure features a central biphenyl unit with methyl substituents at the 3 and 3' positions, linked via imine bonds to two terminal phenyl rings. Each of these outer phenyl rings is attached to a flexible 10-hydroxydecoxy chain, creating a rod-like molecular geometry with hydroxyl-terminated alkyl tails.
A six-membered cyclic ether substituted with a propyl group. Formed by hydrogenation of 4-propylidenetetrahydropyran.

Consisting of a 2-hexyldecyl branched chain and a glucose moiety modified with an imidazolium cation at the primary position, this molecule includes a triethylene glycol spacer ending in an azide group for functionalization.

A three-ring chiral organic ester consisting of a 4'-butyrylbiphenyl-4-carboxylate core connected via an ester linkage to a phenolic moiety that bears a butyl lactate group. The structure features a propyl ketone chain attached to the biphenyl unit and includes a chiral center within the lactate-derived segment.

PPT6BT is an all-aromatic, conjugated triad built from two thiophene rings connected through a five-membered thiadiazole ring (a heteroaromatic ring containing two nitrogens and one sulfur). Each thiophene is substituted with a linear hexyl chain, and one thiophene additionally bears a pendant phenyl ring attached via a carbon–carbon bond.

An asymmetrical molecule synthesized via the condensation of 1,3-benzothiazole-2-carbaldehyde and 4-dodecylaniline. The structure comprises a benzothiazole unit linked to a phenyl ring through an azomethine bridge, with a long dodecyl alkyl chain attached to the para-position of the phenyl ring.

An intermolecular complex comprising a 1:1 molar ratio of 4-(4-(hexyloxyphenylimino)methyl)phenyl nicotinate and 4-dodecyloxybenzoic acid, stabilized by hydrogen bonding between the pyridyl nitrogen atom of the nicotinate moiety and the carboxylic acid group of the benzoic acid derivative, which features a twelve-carbon alkoxy chain.

A tricyclic organic molecule synthesized via a denitrogenative palladium-catalyzed cascade reaction between 2-iodotoluene and 2-bromobenzaldehyde hydrazone. It features a rigid fluorene core substituted with a methyl group at the 1-position.

A lysine derivative featuring a hexanoyl chain at the alpha-nitrogen position, obtained by acylation of alpha-amino-epsilon-caprolactam followed by hydrolysis. The molecule contains a hydrophilic amino acid head group and a short hydrophobic tail.
An unsaturated heterocyclic compound featuring an allyl side chain and a phenyl ester group on a dihydrooxazole ring. Synthesized through a catalytically controlled rearrangement.
A glycerophospholipid with a phosphoethanolamine headgroup, featuring a stearoyl chain at the sn-1 position and an oxidized 9-hydroxyeicosatetraenoyl chain at the sn-2 position.

5-methyl-2-nitrobenzoic acid is an aromatic organic scaffold featuring a rigid core connected by linkers and substituted with flexible side chains. The structure includes heteroatom-containing functional groups and extended conjugation, with substituent patterns defining the overall shape and polarity. Variations in ring composition and terminal groups modulate steric bulk and electronic distribution across the framework.
An anthracycline glycoside antibiotic electrostatically paired with a cis-9-octadecenoic acid anion to enhance lipophilicity.
A disazo dye molecule containing a pyrrolidine electron donor and a butylphenyl group linked through a conjugated phenylene-bis(diazene) system.

Compound 6 is an aromatic organic scaffold featuring a rigid core connected by linkers and substituted with flexible side chains. The structure includes heteroatoms and extended conjugation. Variations in ring composition and terminal groups modulate steric bulk and electronic distribution.

The molecule consists of a central terephthalohydrazide core linked via hydrazone bonds to two terminal 3,4,5-tris(dodecyloxy)benzylidene groups, resulting in a symmetrical structure with a central aromatic ring flanked by two outer aromatic rings, each substituted with three dodecyloxy chains.
A 2,4-dichloro substituted derivative of ethyl 2-cyano-3-phenyl-2-propenoate. This monomer is prepared by the condensation of 2,4-dichlorobenzaldehyde with ethyl cyanoacetate.
An alkenyl-substituted tetrahydropyran prepared from a phosphonium salt and a cyclic ketone.

compound_name: Poly(dodecyl methacrylate-co-poly(ethylene glycol) methyl ether methacrylate)
description: A polymethacrylate-based random copolymer synthesized from dodecyl methacrylate and oligo(ethylene glycol) methyl ether methacrylate, featuring a backbone with pendant hydrophobic alkyl and hydrophilic oligomeric ether side chains.
A gold(III) porphyrin salt comprising a meso-tetrakis(4-icosyloxyphenyl)porphyrin cation coordinated to a gold(III) center, balanced by a tetrafluoroborate anion.

A symmetric organic compound featuring a central 3,5-diphenyl-1,2,4-oxadiazole core, where the phenyl rings at the 3 and 5 positions are substituted with pentanoate ester chains. These chains link the core to two terminal 4-cyanobiphenyl groups.
Poly(p-phenylene vinylene) is an electroluminescent material with amorphous nature or isotropic distribution of crystallites.

An asymmetric biaryl hydrocarbon consisting of a phenyl ring coupled to a 4-methylphenyl group. It is produced by a photochemical splicing reaction where a temporary linker, such as a sulfonamide or thioether connecting the aryl units, is extruded under UV irradiation.

PET-5 is an aromatic scaffold with a rigid core, linkers, and flexible side chains. It features heteroatom groups and extended conjugation, where substituents define shape and polarity. Ring composition and terminal groups modulate steric bulk and electronic distribution.

This compound is a symmetrical bis-benzylidene cyclohexanone analogue prepared via base-catalyzed condensation. Its structure is characterized by a central cyclohexanone core substituted at the alpha-positions with two 4-chlorophenyl groups, creating a conjugated framework with electron-withdrawing chlorine atoms at the para positions.
A halogenated nitrobenzoic acid with a chlorine atom at the 4-position and a nitro group at the 3-position. It is characterized by its ability to form solid solutions.

An aliphatic polyester synthesized via the polycondensation of 1,4-butanediol and adipic acid. It features a linear repeating unit with ester linkages and is commonly used as a crystallizable soft segment in block copolymers.
An isobutyl-substituted poly(vinyl ether) synthesized to demonstrate a sequential cationic-anionic polymerization scope. It shows a single thermal event corresponding to the vitrification point.
Rod-like nanoparticles characterized by a high aspect ratio and negative surface functional groups, such as sulfate esters.

This compound is an acrylanilide derivative characterized by a naphthalene ring attached to the nitrogen atom. It exists as a solid substrate and serves as a model for investigating extended pi-systems.
Fmoc-Diphenylalanine peptide-based compound forming hydrogel.
A semi-synthetic aminoglycoside antibiotic derived from kanamycin A, acylated with an amino-hydroxybutyryl group at the C-1 amino position.

A 1:1 supramolecular complex formed between 4-(4-(hexyloxyphenylimino)methyl)phenyl nicotinate and 4-decyloxybenzoic acid, characterized by intermolecular hydrogen bonding between the pyridine nitrogen of the nicotinate derivative and the carboxylic acid group of the benzoic acid component. The structure features a hexyloxy chain on the imino-linked phenyl ring and a decyloxy chain on the benzoic acid moiety.

Gold nanoparticles functionalized with 4'-((10-mercaptodecyl)oxy)-4-cyanobiphenyl ligands, where the ligand structure consists of a cyanobiphenyl group connected to the gold surface via a decyl spacer and a thiol linkage.

A paramagnetic copper(II) complex of an octakis(ethylsulfanyl)porphyrazine. This open-shell molecular system is studied to determine the influence of the d9 metal center and sulfur atoms on its spectroscopic properties.
A triblock copolymer prepared from 2,4-pyridinedicarboxylic acid and propylene glycol, functionalized with PEG-2000 blocks. The central polyester core contains 2,4-substituted pyridine units.
A widespread triterpenoid acid found in Lantana camara. It contains a rigid pentacyclic core and self-associates into fibers or vesicles depending on the solvent environment.
A bent bidentate ligand consisting of a central benzene ring substituted with two pyridine rings at the 1 and 3 positions.
A redox-active aromatic diol featuring a methoxy substituent, used in energy storage systems and battery applications.

A symmetric azomethine dimer consisting of a central decamethylene spacer linked to two terminal pyrene groups via phenoxy-imine segments, synthesized by the condensation of 1,10-bis(4-formylphenoxy)-decane with 1-aminopyrene.
A methyl ester obtained from the Knoevenagel condensation of hexanal with dimethyl malonate followed by Michael addition.

A dimeric cobalt(II) complex in which two metal centers are bridged by oxygen atoms from 3,6-di-tert-butylcatecholate ligands, with 4,4'-di-tert-butyl-2,2'-bipyridine ligands completing the coordination sphere. Synthesized under anhydrous conditions from cobalt(II) chloride and sodium catecholate. The complex exhibits high-spin magnetic behavior and antiferromagnetic exchange.
A triterpenoid acid obtained from Liquidambar formosana. It possesses a polycyclic backbone and forms three-dimensional fibrillar networks in solvents through non-covalent interactions.

A two-dimensional carbon material composed of sp2-bonded atoms arranged in a hexagonal lattice. It is synthesized via the liquid-phase exfoliation of graphite in an aqueous medium containing sodium dodecyl sulfate as a surfactant. This material is characterized by high surface area and electrical conductivity, serving as a support for metal nanoparticles in catalytic applications.

N-(p-Tolyl)cyclohex-1-ene-1-carboxamide (S30) is an aromatic organic scaffold featuring a rigid core connected by linkers and substituted with flexible side chains. The structure includes heteroatom-containing functional groups and extended conjugation, with substituent patterns defining the overall shape and polarity. Variations in ring composition and terminal groups modulate steric bulk and electronic distribution across the framework.
A riminophenazine dye characterized by a phenazine core substituted with a chlorophenyl group and an isopropylimino moiety.

Estradiol is a steroid built on a fused four-ring (cyclopenta[a]phenanthrene) framework. The A-ring is aromatic and bears a phenolic hydroxyl substituent, while the D-ring carries a secondary alcohol at the 17-position. The remaining rings are saturated and fused in a fixed, polycyclic arrangement with defined stereocenters, including an angular methyl substituent on the steroid core.

A commonly used synthetic transformation to access estradiol from closely related steroids is chemoselective reduction of the 17-ketone in estrone to the corresponding 17-hydroxyl group (stereoselectively giving the 17β alcohol), followed by any required protection/deprotection of the phenolic hydroxyl group to control reactivity during the reduction and workup.

A trisubstituted ethylene derivative synthesized by the piperidine-catalyzed condensation of 2-fluoro-3-methoxybenzaldehyde with isopropyl cyanoacetate. This monomer features a phenyl ring substituted with fluorine and methoxy groups and serves as a precursor for styrene copolymers.

2-methyl-5-nitrobenzoic acid is an aromatic organic scaffold featuring a rigid core connected by linkers and substituted with flexible side chains. The structure includes heteroatom-containing functional groups and extended conjugation, with substituent patterns defining the overall shape and polarity. Variations in ring composition and terminal groups modulate steric bulk and electronic distribution across the framework.
A methacrylate monomer containing a cyanobiphenyl core linked by a hexyl spacer. Synthesized by reacting the corresponding alcohol with methacryloyl chloride.

A long-chain amino acid derivative synthesized from myristoyl chloride and alpha-amino-epsilon-caprolactam. This sodium salt contains a fourteen-carbon alkyl tail at the alpha-position of the lysine backbone.
A methoxy-substituted benzoxazole boron difluoride complex. The molecule comprises a fused heterocyclic system coordinated to boron.
A type 5-specific phosphodiesterase inhibitor encapsulated within the cubosomal formulation for uterine targeting.
A fluorinated azobenzene diol featuring hexyl spacers. It is synthesized via transesterification of the corresponding diethyl ester with 1,6-hexanediol.
A conjugated system featuring an ethyl ester and a cyano group attached to a vinyl unit, which is further substituted by a 4-ethoxyphenyl ring. It acts as a monomer in polymerization reactions.

A steroid-based monomer synthesized by the reaction of a hydroxy-functionalized acrylate derivative with cholesteryl chloroformate. The molecule features a rigid tetracyclic core linked to a polymerizable vinyl group through a flexible hexyl spacer and a carbonate moiety.

A synthetic dipeptide derivative prepared via ring-opening of gamma-benzyl-L-glutamate N-carboxyanhydride using propargylamine as an initiator. The molecule features a terminal alkyne group and two glutamate units with benzyl ester side chains. It serves as a model compound to study the coordination interactions between alkyne functional groups and platinum surfaces.

A bulky cyclotriphosphazene derivative with six bisphenol A-based side arms terminated by methallyl ether groups. It is synthesized to serve as a precursor for epoxy resins, capable of undergoing Claisen rearrangement and subsequent epoxidation.
A saturated fatty acid featuring an eighteen-carbon chain with a terminal carboxyl group. It forms composites with expanded graphite.
A phenolic alcohol derived from the reduction of a lignin-based aldehyde, used as a monomer for bio-based resins.
A semi-synthetic ansamycin antibiotic derived from rifamycin S, distinguishing itself by the presence of a spiro-piperidyl group.

A beta-phosphorylated acrylate ester obtained by the regio- and stereoselective reaction of ethyl propiolate with diphenylphosphine oxide. It features an ethyl ester group and two phenyl rings attached to the phosphorus atom.

A symmetric three-ring aromatic ester comprising a central terephthalate core connected via ester linkages to two 4-butanoyloxyphenyl groups. The molecule features a linear arrangement of three benzene rings, with the central ring flanked by two outer phenyl rings, each substituted at the para position with a butyryl ester chain.
A diterpene acid obtained from pine resin. It contains a hydrophenanthrene ring system and forms spherical nanoparticles via emulsion-solvent evaporation.

N-(4-((trifluoromethyl)thio)phenyl)cyclohex-1-ene-1-carboxamide (S36) is an aromatic organic scaffold featuring a rigid core connected by linkers and substituted with flexible side chains. The structure includes heteroatom-containing functional groups and extended conjugation, with substituent patterns defining the overall shape and polarity. Variations in ring composition and terminal groups modulate steric bulk and electronic distribution across the framework.

n-3O2 is an aromatic organic scaffold with a rigid core, linkers, and flexible side chains. It features heteroatoms and extended conjugation, with substituent patterns defining shape and polarity. Ring composition and terminal groups modulate steric bulk and electronic distribution.
A sterically congested, dichloro-substituted organosilane derivative of a rigid aromatic cage, synthesized to study restricted rotation and rotamerism in solution.
A steroidal sapogenin extracted from Dioscorea Nipponica. It features a spiroketal side chain and forms fibers or rods in self-assembled systems.
A phosphoric acid ester with three ethyl groups attached to the phosphate core. It is utilized as a source of phosphorus in the synthesis of phosphate-containing materials.
A core-modified porphyrin analog where one pyrrole nitrogen atom is replaced by a sulfur atom.

A tetrasubstituted ether derivative of tetraphenylene with methoxy groups at the 2, 7, 10, and 15 positions. Prepared by the dimerization of 2-iodo-4,4'-dimethoxy-1,1'-biphenyl. Serves as a precursor for functionalized saddle-shaped molecules.
A meso-tetraarylporphyrin derivative containing meta-hydroxy groups on the phenyl rings, used as a precursor for further functionalization.
A p-alkoxyphenol ether widely used in industrial and agricultural productions, shown to exhibit relatively strong in vivo estrogenic activity in immature mouse uterotrophic assays.

Synthesized by the reaction of gamma-benzyl-L-glutamate with triphosgene in ethyl acetate. This molecule is an N-carboxyanhydride derivative of an amino acid ester, featuring a 2,5-dioxooxazolidine ring substituted with a benzyl propanoate side chain. It serves as a reactive monomer for the preparation of polypeptides via ring-opening polymerization.

A bis-acylphosphine oxide compound comprising a central phosphorus atom connected to a phenyl ring and two 2,4,6-trimethylbenzoyl moieties. This yellow solid functions as a photoinitiator, generating radicals for polymerization processes.
A triterpenoid derivative extracted from Poria cocos. It forms fibrillar networks and is utilized in constructing injectable scaffolds.
Class III glass former. Retained glassy state under refrigerated conditions but crystallized under high humidity.

N-(4-Ethynylphenyl)cyclohex-1-ene-1-carboxamide (1e) is an aromatic organic scaffold featuring a rigid core connected by linkers and substituted with flexible side chains. The structure includes heteroatom-containing functional groups and extended conjugation, with substituent patterns defining the overall shape and polarity. Variations in ring composition and terminal groups modulate steric bulk and electronic distribution across the framework.
An ester conjugate of retinoic acid and a pinacolone derivative, specifically the 2-hydroxy-3,3-dimethyl-1-butanone ester.
A straight-chain alkyl thiol containing six carbon atoms. It acts as a nucleophile in organic synthesis and can participate in addition reactions at oil-water interfaces to drive droplet motion.

PEF-5S consists of an aromatic organic scaffold with a rigid core, linkers, and flexible side chains. It features heteroatom-containing functional groups and extended conjugation. Variations in ring composition and terminal groups modulate steric bulk and electronic distribution.
A pyrazolopyrimidinone derivative containing a sulfonamide linker connected to a propyl-methylpyrrolidine group.

A semi-synthetic taxoid derivative. Structurally, it consists of a complex taxane ring system substituted with two methoxy groups at positions 7 and 10, distinguishing it from related taxanes. It contains a bulky side chain with a tert-butyl carbamate group attached to a phenylisoserine moiety.

4'-(3-cyclobutylpropoxy)-[1,1'-biphenyl]-4-carbonitrile comprises a biphenyl core substituted with a 4-cyano group and a 4'-(3-cyclobutylpropoxy) ether chain. The molecule features a rigid aromatic system linked to a flexible alkyl tail terminated by a cyclobutane ring.

A cyclotriphosphazene compound bearing six 4-(N-allyliminomethyl)phenoxy groups. It is prepared by the condensation of hexakis(4-formylphenoxy)cyclotriphosphazene with allylamine and is used as a starting material for the synthesis of phosphonate extractants.
An oleanane-type diol derived from dried olive leaves. It organizes into complex flower-like or grass-like fibrillar structures in colloidal suspensions.

An asymmetric perylene-3,4,9,10-tetracarboxylic diimide derivative featuring a rigid planar aromatic core. One imide nitrogen is substituted with a branched 1-heptyloctyl alkyl chain, while the other imide nitrogen bears a branched 1,3-bis(2-(2-(2-methoxyethoxy)ethoxy)ethoxy)propan-2-yl polyether substituent, resulting in an amphiphilic structure with distinct polarity on opposing sides of the perylene framework.

BMe2-PhOC12 is an aromatic organic scaffold featuring a rigid core connected by linkers and substituted with flexible side chains. The structure includes heteroatom functional groups and extended conjugation. Substituent patterns and terminal groups modulate steric bulk and electronic distribution.

Compound 25 is an aromatic organic scaffold featuring a rigid core connected by linkers and substituted with flexible side chains. The structure includes heteroatom-containing functional groups and extended conjugation, with substituent patterns defining the overall shape and polarity. Variations in ring composition and terminal groups modulate steric bulk and electronic distribution across the framework.

A fused-ring organic molecule consisting of a benzothieno[3,2-b]naphtho[2,3-b]thiophene core with an octyl substituent at the 9-position. This structure is obtained via Suzuki coupling and subsequent acid-mediated intramolecular cyclization steps.
An aliphatic polyamide produced from the monomer 12-aminododecanoic acid or laurolactam.
A meso-tetraarylporphyrin derivative substituted with para-tert-butyl groups on the phenyl rings to enhance solubility.

This compound is a glycerophosphocholine based on an sn-glycerol backbone substituted at the sn-1, sn-2, and sn-3 positions. The sn-1 hydroxyl group is esterified with a stearoyl chain, a linear saturated 18-carbon acyl group. The sn-2 hydroxyl group forms an ester linkage with a 5-hydroxyeicosatetraenoyl chain; this 20-carbon acyl chain features four carbon–carbon double bonds and a secondary hydroxyl group located at the C5 position. The sn-3 position is linked via a phosphate diester to a choline moiety, forming a zwitterionic phosphocholine headgroup characterized by a negatively charged phosphate and a positively charged quaternary ammonium group.
A propenoate derivative featuring a 2,4-dimethoxyphenyl group and a cyano substituent on the alkene chain. This molecule serves as a monomeric unit for polymer synthesis.

A cationic lipid based on a propane-1,2-diol backbone that is diesterified at the C1 and C2 positions with oleic acid, and functionalized at the C3 position with a quaternary trimethylammonium headgroup.

An azobenzene-based monomer analogous to long-chain derivatives but possessing shorter octyl spacers linking the central chromophore to polymerizable acrylate termini. It is used to investigate the effect of alkyl chain length on polymer network properties.
A halogenated benzoic acid with a chlorine atom at the 2-position and a nitro group at the 4-position. It forms solid solutions with analogous compounds and crystallizes in the monoclinic system.
The molecule consists of a linear twelve-carbon alkyl chain attached to an ammonium chloride headgroup.
A gold(III) porphyrin salt consisting of a gold(III) cation coordinated to a meso-tetrakis(4-hexadecyloxyphenyl)porphyrin ligand, balanced by a chloride counterion.
A small molecule additive featuring an azobenzene moiety substituted with a carboxylic acid group and a phenol group, used in supramolecular assembly with block copolymers.
A chlorobenzylamino-substituted pyrimidine carboxamide derivative featuring a dihydroxypropylaminomethyl side chain.
A cationic organic salt consisting of a 1-methylimidazolium group tethered to a 4-methylazobenzene unit through an octyloxy chain, accompanied by a bromide anion.
A cyclic analogue of D-alanine. Structurally, it is 4-amino-3-isoxazolidinone produced by Streptomyces garyphalus.

FAST-C20 is an aromatic organic scaffold featuring a rigid core connected by linkers and substituted with flexible side chains. It includes heteroatom-containing functional groups and extended conjugation. Substituent patterns, ring composition, and terminal groups modulate steric bulk and electronic distribution.
A chiral secondary alcohol formed by the stereoselective oxidation of 4-ethylphenol using vanillyl alcohol oxidase.
Formed by the reaction of terephthalohydrazide and 4-dodecyloxybenzaldehyde. The molecule comprises a central terephthalohydrazide core linked to two 4-dodecyloxybenzylidene units.

A heterocyclic organic compound featuring a five-membered oxazolone ring. It possesses a quaternary carbon substituted with a phenyl ester group and an ethyl side chain. Synthesized via an enantiodivergent rearrangement reaction.

A non-steroidal aniline derivative. The molecule comprises a benzene ring substituted with a nitro group and a trifluoromethyl group, linked to an isobutyryl moiety via an amide bond. It is structurally distinct from steroidal compounds.
Heterocyclic monomer copolymerized with PPTA to form ribbon-like nanofiber networks via polymerization-induced self-assembly.

A silicon-based polymer containing carbodiimide units in the backbone and phenyl substituents. Synthesized via pyridine-catalyzed condensation, it serves as a precursor for carbon-rich ceramic nanocomposites.
An asymmetric organic molecule based on a fused [1]benzothieno[3,2-b][1]benzothiophene core, featuring a phenyl ring at one terminus of the conjugated backbone and a decyl alkyl chain at the other.

A 1:1 hydrogen-bonded supramolecular complex formed between 4-[(4-(n-hexyloxy)phenylimino)methyl]benzoic acid and 2-chloro-4-(pyridin-4-ylazo)phenyl 4-hexyloxybenzoate. The assembly consists of a benzoic acid Schiff base acting as a proton donor and a pyridyl-azo ester with a lateral chlorine substituent acting as a proton acceptor.

An organic compound featuring a benzobisthiadiazole core and a butyl acrylate substituent on one of its dimethylthiophene rings, synthesized to demonstrate substrate scope in enantioselective olefination.
A triterpenoid saponin found in Bupleurum species. It exhibits amphiphilic properties, leading to the formation of spherical micelles or nanoparticles.

Ethyl 2-cyano-3-(4-fluorophenyl)-2-propenoate is an aromatic organic scaffold featuring a rigid core connected by linkers and substituted with flexible side chains. The structure includes heteroatom-containing functional groups and extended conjugation, with substituent patterns defining the overall shape and polarity. Variations in ring composition and terminal groups modulate steric bulk and electronic distribution across the framework.
The molecule comprises a central benzo[c][1,2,5]thiadiazole unit flanked by two thiophene rings, each of which is substituted at the 5-position with a 4-hexylphenyl group.

A rod-like diester molecule comprising a central hydroquinone residue esterified by 4-methoxybenzoic acid and 4-nitrobenzoic acid. It is characterized by a polar structure and a tendency to form a modulated orientational state.
A polyamide derivative synthesized from glycine and 6-aminocaproic acid.

Ethyl 2-cyano-3-(3,4-dimethoxyphenyl)-2-propenoate is an aromatic organic scaffold featuring a rigid core connected by linkers and substituted with flexible side chains. The structure includes heteroatom-containing functional groups and extended conjugation, with substituent patterns defining the overall shape and polarity. Variations in ring composition and terminal groups modulate steric bulk and electronic distribution across the framework.

A diamagnetic square-planar nickel(II) chromophore containing 3,6-di-tert-butylcatecholate and 4,4'-di-tert-butyl-2,2'-bipyridine ligands. Prepared by the reaction of bis(cyclooctadiene)nickel(0) with the bipyridine followed by oxidative addition of the corresponding quinone. The structure consists of isolated molecular pairs with a perpendicular mutual arrangement.
A bifunctional azo initiator containing hydroxyl and nitrile groups, used for the synthesis of polymers and the coupling of macromolecular chains.
A nitro-dihydro-imidazooxazole derivative. Structurally, it contains a nitroimidazole ring fused to an oxazole moiety, linked to a phenoxymethyl side chain.

A gallic acid derivative functionalized with three undecyloxy chains, each terminated by an allyl ether group. Synthesized by the alkylation of methyl gallate with 1-(allyloxy)-11-bromoundecane followed by basic hydrolysis of the ester. The molecule features a carboxylic acid head group and three polymerizable terminal alkene moieties attached via flexible aliphatic spacers to the central aromatic ring.

An organophosphorus compound containing a dimethylphosphoryl group conjugated to a styryl moiety, produced via copper-catalyzed hydrophosphorylation. It represents a smaller analogue in the class of alkenylphosphine oxides.
A phenolic aldehyde that serves as a primary aromatic derived from lignin, widely used as a flavoring agent and chemical intermediate.
A sterically crowded alkene derivative with a 2,4,6-trimethoxyphenyl group and a cyano-substituted ethyl ester moiety. It is synthesized for polymer applications.

This molecule features a central 1,4-phenylene ring substituted at the 2 and 3 positions with chlorine atoms. This core is ester-linked at the 1 and 4 positions to two 4-((6-(acryloyloxy)hexyl)oxy)benzoate groups. Each of these benzoate wings consists of a benzene ring attached to a hexyloxy chain, which terminates in an acrylate functional group.

A bent-core organic molecule comprising a central 3-hydroxy-5-methylbenzoic acid derivative core linked via a Schiff base to a 4-octyloxyphenyl arm and via an ester bond to a 2,3,4,5-tetrafluorophenyl group. The molecule features an intramolecular hydrogen bond within the salicylaldimine moiety and possesses a flexible octyloxy terminal chain.
A dithienofuran-based compound bearing 4-chlorophenyl substituents. It is constructed from a dibromo-dialkynylfuran derivative through a copper-mediated reaction scheme.

A saturated, branched hydrocarbon also known as 2,6,10,15,19,23-hexamethyltetracosane. It is produced by the complete hydrogenation of a naturally occurring triterpene. The structure consists of a long aliphatic chain with regularly spaced methyl substituents, functioning as a stable non-polar solvent.

A disubstituted ether derivative featuring two methoxy groups on a tetraphenylene framework. Obtained via statistical cross-coupling methods using palladium catalysis. Exhibits a non-planar saddle geometry common to this class of cyclooctatetraene derivatives.

A temperature-responsive polymer synthesized from N-isopropylacrylamide. The chemical structure consists of a hydrocarbon backbone bearing pendant amide groups substituted with isopropyl chains. It is widely used in hydrogel synthesis due to its solubility changes in water.

A carboxylic acid derivative containing a triphenylene core linked to the benzoate moiety via a dodecyl ether spacer. This molecule serves as a key building block for larger supramolecular architectures, combining a rigid disk-shaped aromatic system with a reactive acid functional group.

An organophosphorus compound comprising a methyl acrylate backbone substituted with a diphenylphosphoryl moiety, prepared through catalytic hydrophosphorylation. The structure is characterized by a conjugate system involving the phosphorus center, the alkene, and the carbonyl group.

A lipophilic cephalosporin derivative synthesized via the esterification of cefuroxime sodium with n-dodecan-1-ol using HBTU as a coupling agent. The molecular structure features a beta-lactam ring fused to a dihydrothiazine ring, bearing a carbamoyloxymethyl group and a furyl-methoxyiminoacetamido side chain, with the carboxylic acid functionality converted to a twelve-carbon alkyl ester.
A brominated N-methyl phenanthridinone derivative. It is a solid product formed by the photocyclization of N-(4-bromophenyl)-N-methylcyclohex-1-ene-1-carboxamide.
A star-shaped organic molecule featuring an ethene core substituted with four phenyl rings, each of which is para-substituted with a pyridine moiety.

A supramolecular assembly consisting of a 1:1 complex formed between 4-(4-(hexyloxyphenylimino)methyl)phenyl nicotinate and 4-hexadecyloxybenzoic acid. The structure is stabilized by hydrogen bonding between the pyridine nitrogen atom of the nicotinate derivative and the carboxylic acid group of the benzoic acid derivative, which features a sixteen-carbon alkoxy chain at the para position.

A peptide derivative comprising a hexadecanoyl (palmitoyl) chain attached to the N-terminus of a nonapeptide sequence consisting of six consecutive L-alanine residues followed by three consecutive L-glutamic acid residues. The molecule features a long aliphatic hydrocarbon tail and a peptide backbone terminating in three free carboxylic acid groups.

A methacrylate monomer bearing a hydrophilic hydroxyl group. It is utilized in polymerization reactions to create amphiphilic polymers that can undergo self-organization into various morphologies within aqueous dispersions.

A photoswitchable molecule comprising a central benzobisthiadiazole moiety bridging two dimethylthiophene rings, one of which is functionalized with a methyl acrylate group through an enantioselective reaction.

A quaternary ammonium salt containing a hydroxyethyl group. It acts as a hydrogen bond acceptor in the formation of deep eutectic solvents and is synthesized via the reaction of trimethylamine, hydrochloric acid, and ethylene oxide.
A heptapeptide comprising a hexameric L-alanine sequence followed by a C-terminal L-lysine residue, modified by N-terminal acetylation and C-terminal amidation.
A nitrile compound derived from lignin, synthesized via the dehydration of an aldoxime precursor.

The hydrochloride salt form of a morphinan-type alkaloid. The structure features a rigid tetracyclic core with a protonated tertiary amine, an enone system, and ether functionalities, paired with a chloride counterion. This ionic formulation serves to enhance aqueous solubility.

A diethylphosphoryl-substituted styrene derivative, obtained by the addition of diethylphosphine oxide to phenylacetylene under oxidative conditions. It features ethyl groups on the phosphorus atom instead of phenyl rings.

A symmetric dimer synthesized via condensation of 1,4-bis(4-formylphenoxy)-butane with aniline. Features two terminal phenyl rings connected to a central bis(phenoxy)butane core through imine linkages. A rigid rod-like organic molecule.

i-3O3 is an aromatic organic scaffold featuring a rigid core connected by linkers and substituted with flexible side chains. The structure includes heteroatom-containing functional groups and extended conjugation. Ring composition and terminal groups modulate steric bulk and electronic distribution.

An azobenzene derivative characterized by a push-pull electronic structure with a nitro electron-withdrawing group and an amino electron-donating group. One of the N-alkyl chains is functionalized with an acrylate ester, allowing the dye to be covalently incorporated into polymer chains during synthesis.

A hydrogen-bonded supramolecular assembly comprising a 4-hexyloxyphenylazobenzoic acid donor and a 4-(4'-pyridylazophenyl)-4''-octyloxybenzoate acceptor. The complex features an extended linear geometry stabilized by the interaction between the carboxylic acid and pyridine moieties, incorporating azobenzene units and terminal hexyloxy and octyloxy chains.
HOBA. Forms hydrogen bonded dimers in the crystalline state.
Prepared by the alkylation of the phenolic precursor with 1,6-dibromohexane. It consists of a diphenyl-diacetylene conjugated system flanked by a dodecyloxy chain and a bromohexyloxy chain.

A saturated triglyceride formed by the esterification of glycerol with three molecules of myristic acid. It is a symmetric lipid molecule characterized by three long aliphatic chains attached to a glycerol backbone.
An organic acid derivative synthesized by the etherification of 4-hydroxybenzoic acid with 6-bromo-1-hexanol. It contains a carboxylic acid group and a terminal hydroxyl group on an alkyl chain.
An ethyl ether derivative of cellulose utilized to form porous, broadband scattering films via evaporation-induced phase separation.

RM1041 is an aromatic scaffold featuring a rigid core connected by linkers to flexible side chains. The structure exhibits extended conjugation and heteroatom functional groups, with substituents defining shape and polarity. Ring composition and terminal groups adjust the steric bulk and electronic distribution.

A macrocyclic compound synthesized via the condensation of diaminodibenzo-18-crown-6 with 1-pyrenecarboxaldehyde. The structure consists of a dibenzo-18-crown-6 ether core substituted with two pyrene moieties linked through imine bonds on the phenyl rings. The molecule contains a polyether ring capable of coordinating metal ions and extended aromatic systems facilitating pi-stacking interactions.
A linear anionic polysaccharide copolymer consisting of 1,4-linked beta-D-mannuronic acid and alpha-L-guluronic acid residues arranged in blocks.

A polycyclic aromatic tetraol featuring four hydroxyl groups on a tetraphenylene core. Produced by the demethylation of the corresponding tetramethoxy compound. Possesses a saddle-shaped structure capable of hydrogen bonding.

n-3O3 consists of a rigid aromatic core connected by linkers and substituted with flexible side chains. The structure features heteroatom-containing functional groups and extended conjugation. Variations in ring composition and terminal groups modulate the steric bulk and electronic distribution.
An ethyl 2-cyanoacrylate derivative containing a phenyl ring with a para-propoxy substituent. This compound is synthesized for use in creating functionalized copolymers.

A carboxylic ester resulting from the formal condensation of the carboxy group of 4'-pentanoylbiphenyl-4-carboxylic acid with the hydroxy group of hexyl (S)-2-(4-hydroxyphenoxy)propanoate. It features a biphenyl core substituted at the 4'-position with a pentanoyl group and at the 4-position with an ester linkage connecting to a phenyl ring. This phenyl ring is further substituted at the para position with an ester-linked (S)-1-(hexyloxy)-1-oxopropan-2-yl group, containing a chiral center within the lactate-derived moiety.

A derivative of a natural polysaccharide synthesized via amide coupling of chitosan oligosaccharide with a fatty acid using carbodiimide activation. The structure comprises a hydrophilic sugar backbone randomly substituted with long-chain hydrophobic alkenyl tails.
A phosphatidylcholine 3-sn-glycerophosphocholine derivative in which the sn-1 position is acylated by stearic acid, while the sn-2 position is acylated by 8-hydroxyeicosatetraenoic acid.
A carboxylic acid derivative of vitamin A, featuring a beta-ionone ring attached to a conjugated polyene chain ending in a carboxylic acid functional group.
